[/wiki/2011_European_Fencing_Championships]Team foil\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAnja Mller-Schache (born 29 March 1977) is a German foil fencer\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Foil_fencer].[2] She won a bronze medal, as a member of the German\\\\\\\\nfencing team, at the 2009 World Fencing Championships\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/2009_World_Fencing_Championships] in Antalya, Turkey\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Antalya,_Turkey].[3]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSchache represented Germany [/wiki/Germany] at the 2008 Summer Olympics\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/2008_Summer_Olympics] in Beijing [/wiki/Beijing], where she competed in\\\\\\\\ntwo foil events. For her first event, the women's individual foil\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Fencing_at_the_2008_Summer_Olympics_%E2%80%93_Women%27s_foil], Schache\\\\\\\\nreceived a bye for the second preliminary round match, before losing out to\\\\\\\\nRussia's Evgenia Lamonova [/wiki/Evgenia_Lamonova], with a score of 215.[4] Few\\\\\\\\ndays later, she joined with her fellow fencers and teammates Melanie Wolgast,\\\\\\\\nKatja Wchter [/wiki/Katja_W%C3%A4chter], and Carolin Golubytskyi\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Carolin_Golubytskyi] for the women's team foil\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Fencing_at_the_2008_Summer_Olympics_%E2%80%93_Women%27s_team_foil].\\\\\\\\nSchache and her team, however, lost the fifth place match to the Chinese team\\\\\\\\n(led by Zhang Lei [/wiki/Zhang_Lei_(fencing)]), with a total score of 28\\\\\\\\ntouches.[5]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nREFERENCES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Anja_Schache&action=edit&section=1]]\\\\\\\\n 1. ^ a b \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Deutsche Fechter Bund  Anja Schache\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n    [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727172726/http://biographie.fechten.org/fechter/anja.schache]\\\\\\\\n    (in German). encyclopedia\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Category.svg/120px-Category.svg.png]\\\\\\\\nThis is a tracking category [/wiki/Category:Tracking_categories].\\\\\\\\nIt is used to build and maintain a list or lists of pagesprimarily for the sake\\\\\\\\nof the lists themselves and their use in article and category maintenance. It is\\\\\\\\nnot part of the encyclopedia's categorization scheme\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Categorization].\\\\\\\\nMore information:\\\\\\\\n * This category is hidden [/wiki/Wikipedia:Categorization#Hiding_categories] on\\\\\\\\n   its member pages [/wiki/Category:Hidden_categories]unless the corresponding\\\\\\\\n   user preference [/wiki/Special:Preferences#mw-prefsection-rendering]\\\\\\\\n   (Appearance  Show hidden categories) is set.\\\\\\\\n * These categories are used to track, build and organize lists of pages needing\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"attention en masse\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (for example, pages using deprecated syntax), or that\\\\\\\\n   may need to be edited at someone's earliest convenience.\\\\\\\\n * These categories also serve to aggregate members of several lists or\\\\\\\\n   subcategories into a larger, more efficient list (discriminated by\\\\\\\\n   classifications).\\\\\\\\n * Typically, tracking categories are automatically populated by templates\\\\\\\\n   invoked in pages or by the MediaWiki software (see Special:TrackingCategories\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Special:TrackingCategories] for an overview of the latter).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/40px-Ambox_important.svg.png]Administrators:\\\\\\\\nPlease do not delete this category as empty!\\\\\\\\nThis category may be empty occasionally or even most of the time.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe main page for this category [/wiki/Help:Categories] is WP:Short description\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Short_description].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThis category contains articles with short descriptions that do not match the\\\\\\\\ndescription field on Wikidata.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nNo action is needed at this time. This is a tracking category only.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nContents: Kennedy [/wiki/John_F._Kennedy] as an\\\\\\\\nexample. \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"First names\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" can also be called given names, forenames, or, in some\\\\\\\\nplaces at some times, Christian names; \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"last names\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" can also be called family\\\\\\\\nnames or surnames [/wiki/Surname]. This shows a structure typical for\\\\\\\\nEnglish-speaking cultures (and some others). Other cultures use other structures\\\\\\\\nfor full\\\\\\\\nnames.[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Desideria_of_Sweden_%26_Norway_grave_2007.jpg/250px-Desideria_of_Sweden_%26_Norway_grave_2007.jpg]/wiki/File:Desideria_of_Sweden_%26_Norway_grave_2007.jpgThe\\\\\\\\nsarcophagus at Riddarholm Church [/wiki/Riddarholm_Church] in Sweden of Queen\\\\\\\\nDesideria [/wiki/Queen_Desideria], an official name given to Dsire Clary\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/D%C3%A9sir%C3%A9e_Clary] not at birth but when she was elected Crown\\\\\\\\nPrincess of Sweden [/wiki/Crown_princess_of_Sweden] in 1810.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA given name (also known as a forename or first name) is the part of a personal\\\\\\\\nname [/wiki/Personal_name][1] that identifies a person, potentially with a\\\\\\\\nmiddle name [/wiki/Middle_name] as well, and differentiates that person from the\\\\\\\\nother members of a group (typically a family [/wiki/Family] or clan\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Clan]) who have a common surname [/wiki/Surname]. The term given name\\\\\\\\nrefers to a name [/wiki/Name] usually bestowed at or close to the time of birth,\\\\\\\\nusually by the parents of the newborn. A Christian name [/wiki/Christian_name]\\\\\\\\nis the first name which is given at baptism [/wiki/Baptism], in Christian\\\\\\\\ncustom.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn informal situations, given names are often used in a familiar and friendly\\\\\\\\nmanner.[1] In more formal situations, a person's surname is more commonly used.\\\\\\\\nThe idioms 'on a first-name basis\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/on_a_first-name_basis#English]' and 'being on\\\\\\\\nfirst-name terms' refer to the familiarity inherent[Western culture-centric\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Countering_systemic_bias]] in addressing someone by\\\\\\\\ntheir given name.[1]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nBy contrast, a surname (also known as a family name, last name, or gentile name\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Gentile_name]) is normally inherited and shared with other members of\\\\\\\\none's immediate family.[2] Regnal names [/wiki/Regnal_name] and religious or\\\\\\\\nmonastic names [/wiki/Religious_name] are special given names bestowed upon\\\\\\\\nsomeone receiving a crown or entering a religious order; such a person then\\\\\\\\ntypically becomes known chiefly by that name.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nNAME ORDER\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=1]]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Personal name Name order [/wiki/Personal_name#Name_order]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe order given name  family name, commonly known as Western name order, is\\\\\\\\nused throughout most European [/wiki/Europe] countries and in countries that\\\\\\\\nhave cultures predominantly influenced by European culture, including North\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/North_America] and South America [/wiki/South_America]; North\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/North_India], East [/wiki/East_India], Central [/wiki/Central_India] and\\\\\\\\nWest India [/wiki/Western_India]; Australia [/wiki/Australia], New Zealand\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/New_Zealand], and the Philippines [/wiki/Philippines].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe order family name  given name, commonly known as Eastern name order, is\\\\\\\\nprimarily used in East Asia [/wiki/East_Asia] (for example in China\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/China], Japan [/wiki/Japan], Korea [/wiki/Korea], Taiwan [/wiki/Taiwan],\\\\\\\\nSingapore [/wiki/Singapore], and Vietnam [/wiki/Vietnam], among others, and by\\\\\\\\nMalaysian Chinese [/wiki/Malaysian_Chinese]), as well as in Southern\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/South_India] and North-Eastern [/wiki/Northeast_India] parts of India\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/India], and as a standard in Hungary [/wiki/Hungary]. This order is also\\\\\\\\nused to various degrees and in specific contexts in other European countries,\\\\\\\\nsuch as Austria [/wiki/Austria] and adjacent areas of Germany [/wiki/Germany]\\\\\\\\n(that is, Bavaria [/wiki/Bavaria]),[note 1] and in France [/wiki/France],\\\\\\\\nSwitzerland [/wiki/Switzerland], Belgium [/wiki/Belgium], Greece [/wiki/Greece]\\\\\\\\nand Italy [/wiki/Italy][citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]],\\\\\\\\npossibly because of the influence of bureaucracy, which commonly puts the family\\\\\\\\nname before the given name. In China and Korea, part of the given name\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Generation_name] may be shared among all members of a given generation\\\\\\\\nwithin a family and extended family or families, in order to differentiate those\\\\\\\\ngenerations from other generations.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe order given name  father's family name  mother's family name is commonly\\\\\\\\nused in several Spanish [/wiki/Spanish_language]-speaking countries to\\\\\\\\nacknowledge the families of both parents.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe order given name  mother's family name  father's family name is commonly\\\\\\\\nused in Portuguese [/wiki/Portuguese_language]-speaking countries to acknowledge\\\\\\\\nthe families of both parents. Today, people in Spain and Uruguay can rearrange\\\\\\\\nthe order of their names legally to this order.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe order given name  father's given name  grandfather's given name (often\\\\\\\\nreferred to as triple name) is the official naming order used in Arabic\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Arabic] countries (for example Saudi Arabia [/wiki/Saudi_Arabia], Iraq\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Iraq] and United Arab Emirates [/wiki/United_Arab_Emirates]).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCOMPOUND\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=2]]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Compound surname [/wiki/Surname#Compound_surnames] and Double surname\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Double-barrelled_name]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Double name\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" redirects here; not to be confused with Double place naming\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Dual_naming], Tautonym [/wiki/Tautonym], or Reduplication\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Reduplication].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn many Western cultures [/wiki/Western_culture], people often have multiple\\\\\\\\ngiven names. Most often the first one in sequence is the one that a person goes\\\\\\\\nby, although exceptions are not uncommon, such as in the cases of John Edgar\\\\\\\\nHoover [/wiki/John_Edgar_Hoover] (J. Edgar) and Dame Mary Barbara Hamilton\\\\\\\\nCartland [/wiki/Dame_Mary_Barbara_Hamilton_Cartland] (Barbara).The given name\\\\\\\\nmight also be used in compound form, as in, for example, John Paul\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/John_Paul_(given_name)] or a hyphenated style like Bengt-Arne\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Bengt-Arne_Wallin]. A middle name [/wiki/Middle_name] might be part of a\\\\\\\\ncompound given name or might be, instead, a maiden name [/wiki/Maiden_name], a\\\\\\\\npatronymic [/wiki/Patronymic], or a baptismal name [/wiki/Baptismal_name].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Alexander_Graham_Bell_%28signature%29.svg/330px-Alexander_Graham_Bell_%28signature%29.svg.png]/wiki/File:Alexander_Graham_Bell_(signature).svgThe\\\\\\\\nsignature of Alexander Graham Bell [/wiki/Alexander_Graham_Bell].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn England, it was unusual for a person to have more than one given name until\\\\\\\\nthe seventeenth century when Charles James Stuart (King Charles I\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Charles_I_of_England]) was baptised with two names. That was a French\\\\\\\\nfashion, which spread to the English aristocracy, following the royal example,\\\\\\\\nthen spread to the general population and became common by the end of the\\\\\\\\neighteenth century.[3]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSome double-given names for women were used at the start of the eighteenth\\\\\\\\ncentury but were used together as a unit: Anna Maria, Mary Anne and Sarah Jane.\\\\\\\\nThose became stereotyped as the typical names of servants and so became\\\\\\\\nunfashionable in the nineteenth century.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDouble names remain popular in the Southern United States\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Southern_United_States].[4]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDouble names are also common among Vietnamese names [/wiki/Vietnamese_names] to\\\\\\\\nmake repeated name in the family. For example, ng V Minh Anh and ng V Minh\\\\\\\\nnh, are two sisters with the given names Minh Anh and Minh nh.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nINITIALS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=3]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSometimes, a given name is used as just an initial, especially in combination\\\\\\\\nwith the middle initial (such as with H. G. Wells [/wiki/H._G._Wells]), and more\\\\\\\\nrarely as an initial while the middle name is not one (such as with L. Ron\\\\\\\\nHubbard [/wiki/L._Ron_Hubbard]).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLEGAL STATUS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=4]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA child's given name or names are usually chosen by the parents soon after\\\\\\\\nbirth. If a name is not assigned at birth, one may be given at a naming ceremony\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Naming_ceremony], with family and friends in attendance. In most\\\\\\\\njurisdictions, a child's name at birth is a matter of public record, inscribed\\\\\\\\non a birth certificate [/wiki/Birth_certificate], or its equivalent. In Western\\\\\\\\ncultures, people normally retain the same given name throughout their lives.\\\\\\\\nHowever, in some cases these names may be changed by following legal processes\\\\\\\\nor by repute. People may also change their names when immigrating from one\\\\\\\\ncountry to another with different naming conventions.[5]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn certain jurisdictions, a government-appointed registrar of births may refuse\\\\\\\\nto register a name for the reasons that it may cause a child harm, that it is\\\\\\\\nconsidered offensive, or if it is deemed impractical. In France, the agency can\\\\\\\\nrefer the case to a local judge. Some jurisdictions, such as Sweden, restrict\\\\\\\\nthe spelling of names.[note 2] In Denmark, one does not need to register a given\\\\\\\\nname for the child until the child is six months old, and in some cases, one can\\\\\\\\neven wait a little longer than this before the child gets an official name.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nORIGINS AND MEANINGS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=5]]\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3f/Yohanan_name_evolution.svg/500px-Yohanan_name_evolution.svg.png]/wiki/File:Yohanan_name_evolution.svgJohn\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/John#English], a name of Hebrew origin is very\\\\\\\\npopular in the Western World, and has given many variants depending on the\\\\\\\\nlanguage: Shaun [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Shaun#English], Eoin\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Eoin#Irish], Ian\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Ian#English], Juan\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Juan#English], Ivan\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Ivan#English], and Yahya\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Yahya#English]. Click on the image to see the\\\\\\\\ndiagram in full detail.\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/40px-Ambox_important.svg.png]\\\\\\\\nThis section possibly contains original research\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research]. Please improve it\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit] by verifying\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability] the claims made and adding inline citations\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources#Inline_citations]. Statements consisting only of\\\\\\\\noriginal research should be removed. (June 2020) (Learn how and when to remove\\\\\\\\nthis message [/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal])\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nParents may choose a name because of its meaning. This may be a personal or\\\\\\\\nfamilial meaning, such as giving a child the name of an admired person, or it\\\\\\\\nmay be an example of nominative determinism [/wiki/Nominative_determinism], in\\\\\\\\nwhich the parents give the child a name that they believe will be lucky or\\\\\\\\nfavourable for the child. Given names most often derive from the following\\\\\\\\ncategories:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Aspirational personal traits (external and internal). For example, the male\\\\\\\\n   names:\\\\\\\\n   * Clement (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"merciful\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\");[7][8] as popularised by Pope Clement I\\\\\\\\n     [/wiki/Pope_Clement_I] (8898), saint, and his many papal successors of\\\\\\\\n     that name;\\\\\\\\n   * Augustus (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"consecrated, holy\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"[9]), first popularised by the first Roman\\\\\\\\n     Emperor; later (as Augustine) by two saints;\\\\\\\\n   * English examples include numerous female names such as Faith [/wiki/Faith],\\\\\\\\n     Prudence [/wiki/Prudence], Amanda [/wiki/Amanda] (Latin: worthy of love);\\\\\\\\n     Blanche (white (pure));\\\\\\\\n * Occupations, for example George [/wiki/George_(given_name)] means\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"earth-worker\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", i.e., \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"farmer\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[10]\\\\\\\\n * Circumstances of birth, for example:\\\\\\\\n   * Thomas [/wiki/Thomas_(name)] meaning \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"twin\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\";\\\\\\\\n   * Quintus [/wiki/Quintus] (Latin: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"fifth\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), which was traditionally given to\\\\\\\\n     the fifth male child.[11][12]\\\\\\\\n * Objects, for example Peter [/wiki/Peter_(name)] means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"rock\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" and Edgar\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Edgar] means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"rich spear\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[13][14]\\\\\\\\n * Physical characteristics, for example Calvin [/wiki/Calvin_(given_name)]\\\\\\\\n   means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"bald\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[15]\\\\\\\\n * Variations on another name, especially to change the sex of the name (Pauline\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Pauline_(name)], Georgia) or to adapt from another language (for\\\\\\\\n   instance, the names Francis [/wiki/Francis_(given_name)] or Francisco\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Francisco] that come from the name Franciscus [/wiki/Franciscus]\\\\\\\\n   meaning \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Frank [/wiki/Franks] or Frenchman\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\").[16][17][18]\\\\\\\\n * Surnames, Such names can honour other branches of a family, where the surname\\\\\\\\n   would not otherwise be passed down (e.g., the mother's maiden surname).\\\\\\\\n   Modern examples include:\\\\\\\\n   * Winston,[19]\\\\\\\\n   * Harrison [/wiki/Harrison_(name)],[20]\\\\\\\\n   * Ross [/wiki/Ross_(name)].[21]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMany were adopted from the 17th century in England to show respect to notable\\\\\\\\nancestry, usually given to nephews or male grandchildren of members of the great\\\\\\\\nfamilies concerned, from which the usage spread to general society. This was\\\\\\\\nregardless of whether the family name concerned was in danger of dying out, for\\\\\\\\nexample with Howard, a family with many robust male lines over history. Notable\\\\\\\\nexamples include\\\\\\\\n * * Howard, from the Howard family, Dukes of Norfolk;\\\\\\\\n   * Courtenay, from the surname of the Earls of Devon;\\\\\\\\n   * Trevor, from the Welsh chieftain Tudor Trevor, lord of Hereford;[22]\\\\\\\\n   * Clifford, from the Barons Clifford;\\\\\\\\n   * Digby, from the family of Baron Digby/Earl of Bristol;\\\\\\\\n   * Shirley (originally a man's forename), from the Shirley family, Earls\\\\\\\\n     Ferrer;\\\\\\\\n   * Percy, from the Percy Earls and Dukes of Northumberland;\\\\\\\\n   * Lindsay, from that noble Scottish family, Earls of Crawford;\\\\\\\\n   * Graham, from that noble Scottish family, Dukes of Montrose;\\\\\\\\n   * Eliot, from the Eliot family, Earls of St Germans;\\\\\\\\n   * Herbert, from the Herbert family, Earls of Pembroke;\\\\\\\\n   * Russell, from the Russell family, Earls and Dukes of Bedford;\\\\\\\\n   * Stanley, from the Stanley family, Earls of Derby;\\\\\\\\n   * Vernon, Earl of Shipbrook\\\\\\\\n   * Dillon, the Irish family of Dillon, Viscount Dillon\\\\\\\\n * Places, for example Brittany [/wiki/Brittany][23] and Lorraine\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Duchy_of_Lorraine].[24]\\\\\\\\n * Time of birth, for example, day of the week, as in Kofi Annan\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Kofi_Annan], whose given name means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"born on Friday\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",[25] or the\\\\\\\\n   holiday on which one was born, for example, the name Natalie\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Natalie_(given_name)] meaning \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"born on Christmas [/wiki/Christmas]\\\\\\\\n   day\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" in Latin[26] (Noel (French \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Christmas\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), a name given to males born at\\\\\\\\n   Christmas); also April [/wiki/April_(given_name)], May\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/May_(given_name)], or June [/wiki/June_(given_name)].\\\\\\\\n * Combination of the above, for example the Armenian [/wiki/Armenian_language]\\\\\\\\n   name Sirvart means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"love rose\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[27]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn many cultures, given names are reused, especially to commemorate ancestors\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Namesake] or those who are particularly admired, resulting in a limited\\\\\\\\nrepertoire of names that sometimes vary by orthography [/wiki/Orthography].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe most familiar example of this, to Western readers, is the use of Biblical\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Biblical] and saints' [/wiki/Saint] names in most of the Christian\\\\\\\\ncountries (with Ethiopia, in which names were often ideals or abstractionsHaile\\\\\\\\nSelassie, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"power of the Trinity\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"; Haile Miriam, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"power of Mary\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"as the most\\\\\\\\nconspicuous exception). However, the name Jesus [/wiki/Jesus_(name)] is\\\\\\\\nconsidered taboo [/wiki/Taboo] or sacrilegious [/wiki/Sacrilege] in some parts\\\\\\\\nof the Christian world [/wiki/Christian_world], though this taboo does not\\\\\\\\nextend to the cognate Joshua [/wiki/Joshua] or related forms which are common in\\\\\\\\nmany languages even among Christians. In some Spanish-speaking countries, the\\\\\\\\nname Jesus is considered a normal given name.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSimilarly, the name Mary [/wiki/Mary,_the_mother_of_Jesus], now popular among\\\\\\\\nChristians, particularly Roman Catholics [/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Church], was\\\\\\\\nconsidered too holy for secular use until about the 12th century. In countries\\\\\\\\nthat particularly venerated Mary, this remained the case much longer; in Poland,\\\\\\\\nuntil the arrival in the 17th century of French queens named Marie.[28]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMost common given names in English (and many other European languages) can be\\\\\\\\ngrouped into broad categories based on their origin:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Hebrew names [/wiki/Hebrew_name], most often from the Bible, are very common\\\\\\\\n   in, or are elements of names used in historically Christian countries. Some\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Theophoric_name] have elements meaning \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"God\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", especially \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Eli\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Eli_(name)]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". Examples: Michael [/wiki/Michael_(given_name)], Joshua\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Joshua], Daniel [/wiki/Daniel_(biblical_figure)], Joseph\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Joseph_(Hebrew_Bible)], David [/wiki/David], Adam [/wiki/Adam_(name)],\\\\\\\\n   Samuel [/wiki/Samuel], Elizabeth [/wiki/Elizabeth_(given_name)], Hannah\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Hannah_(given_name)] and Mary [/wiki/Mary_(given_name)]. There are\\\\\\\\n   also a handful of names in use derived from the Aramaic\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Aramaic_language], particularly the names of prominent figures in the\\\\\\\\n   New Testamentsuch as Thomas [/wiki/Thomas_the_Apostle], Martha\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Martha] and Bartholomew [/wiki/Bartholomew].\\\\\\\\n   * All of the Semitic peoples [/wiki/Semitic_people] of history and the\\\\\\\\n     present day use at least some names constructed like these in Hebrew (and\\\\\\\\n     the ancient Hebrews used names not constructed like thesesuch as Moses\\\\\\\\n     [/wiki/Moses], probably an Egyptian name related to the names of Pharaohs\\\\\\\\n     [/wiki/Pharaoh] like Thutmose and Ahmose). The Muslim world is the\\\\\\\\n     best-known example (with names like Saif-al-din, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"sword of the faith\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", or\\\\\\\\n     Abd-Allah, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"servant of God\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), but even the Carthaginians had similar names:\\\\\\\\n     cf. Hannibal, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"the grace of god\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (in this case not the Abrahamic deity God,\\\\\\\\n     but the deityprobably Melkart [/wiki/Melkart]whose title is normally left\\\\\\\\n     untranslated, as Baal [/wiki/Baal]).\\\\\\\\n * Germanic names [/wiki/Germanic_names] are characteristically warlike; roots\\\\\\\\n   with meanings like \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"glory\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"strength\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"will\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" are common. The \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"-bert\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Bert_(name)]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" element common in many such names comes from beraht,\\\\\\\\n   which means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"bright [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/bright]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". Examples:\\\\\\\\n   Robert [/wiki/Robert], Edward [/wiki/Edward], Roger [/wiki/Roger], Richard\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Richard], Albert, Carl, Alfred, Rosalind, Emma, Emmett, Eric\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Eric] and Matilda [/wiki/Matilda_(name)].\\\\\\\\n * French forms of Germanic [/wiki/Germanic_languages] names. Since the Norman\\\\\\\\n   conquest of England [/wiki/Norman_conquest_of_England], many English-given\\\\\\\\n   names of Germanic [/wiki/Germanic_languages] origin are used in their French\\\\\\\\n   forms [/wiki/French_name]. Examples: Charles [/wiki/Charles], Henry\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Henry_(given_name)], William [/wiki/William].\\\\\\\\n * Slavic names [/wiki/Slavic_names] may be of peaceful character, the compounds\\\\\\\\n   being derived from the word roots [/wiki/Root_(linguistics)] meaning \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"to\\\\\\\\n   protect\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"to love\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"peace\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"to praise [gods]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"to give\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". Examples:\\\\\\\\n   Milena [/wiki/Milena_(name)], Vesna [/wiki/Vesna_(name)], Bohumil\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Bohumil], Dobromir [/wiki/Dobromir_(given_name)], Svetlana\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Svetlana], Vlastimil [/wiki/Vlastimil]. Other names have a warlike\\\\\\\\n   character and are built of words meaning \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"fighter\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"war\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"anger\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".\\\\\\\\n   Examples: Casimir [/wiki/Casimir], Vladimir [/wiki/Vladimir_(name)], Sambor\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Sambor_(disambiguation)], Wojciech [/wiki/Wojciech] and Zbigniew\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Zbigniew]. Many of them derive from the root word \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"slava\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"glory\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"):\\\\\\\\n   Boleslav [/wiki/Boleslaus], Miroslav [/wiki/Miroslav_(given_name)], Vladislav\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Vladislav], Radoslav [/wiki/Radoslav_(disambiguation)], Slavomir\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Slavomir] and Stanislav [/wiki/Stanislav_(given_name)]. Those derived\\\\\\\\n   from root word \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"mir\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"world, peace\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") are also popular: Casimir\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Casimir], Slavomir [/wiki/Slavomir], Radomir\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Radomir_(given_name)], Vladimir [/wiki/Vladimir_(name)], Miroslav\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Miroslav_(given_name)], Jaczemir.\\\\\\\\n * Celtic [/wiki/Celtic_languages] names are sometimes anglicised\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Anglicisation] versions of Celtic forms [/wiki/Celtic_language], but\\\\\\\\n   the original form may also be used. Examples: Alan [/wiki/Alan_(name)], Brian\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Brian], Brigid [/wiki/Brigid], Mrag, Ross, Logan\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Logan_(given_name)], Ciarn [/wiki/Ciar%C3%A1n], Jennifer\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Jennifer_(given_name)], and Sen\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/John_(name)#Evolution_of_the_name_John]. These names often have\\\\\\\\n   origins in Celtic words, as Celtic versions of the names of internationally\\\\\\\\n   known Christian [/wiki/Christianity] saints [/wiki/Saint], as names of Celtic\\\\\\\\n   mythological figures [/wiki/Celtic_mythology], or simply as long-standing\\\\\\\\n   names whose ultimate etymology is unclear.\\\\\\\\n * Greek names [/wiki/Greek_names] may be derived from the history and mythology\\\\\\\\n   of Classical Antiquity [/wiki/Classical_Antiquity] or be derived from the New\\\\\\\\n   Testament [/wiki/New_Testament] and early Christian traditions. Such names\\\\\\\\n   are often, but not always, anglicised. Examples: Helen\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Helen_(given_name)], Stephen [/wiki/Stephen], Alexander\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Alexander], Andrew [/wiki/Andrew], Peter [/wiki/Peter_(name)], Gregory\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Gregory_(given_name)], George [/wiki/George_(given_name)], Christopher\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Christopher_(name)], Margaret [/wiki/Margaret_(name)], Nicholas\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Nicholas], Jason [/wiki/Jason_(name)], Timothy [/wiki/Timothy_(name)],\\\\\\\\n   Chloe [/wiki/Chloe], Zo [/wiki/Zoe_(name)], Katherine\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Katherine_(given_name)], Penelope [/wiki/Penelope] and Theodore\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Theodore_(given_name)].\\\\\\\\n * Latin names [/wiki/Roman_naming_conventions] can also be adopted unchanged,\\\\\\\\n   or modified; in particular, the inflected element can be dropped, as often\\\\\\\\n   happens in borrowings from Latin to English. Examples: Laura\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Laura_(name)], Victoria [/wiki/Victoria_(name)], Mark\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Mark_(given_name)] (Latin Marcus [/wiki/Marcus_(name)]), Justin\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Justin_(given_name)] (Latin Justinus), Paul [/wiki/Paul_(name)] (Lat.\\\\\\\\n   Paulus), Julius, Julia [/wiki/Julia_(given_name)], Cecilia, Felix\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Felix_(name)], Vivian [/wiki/Vivian_(personal_name)], Pascal\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Pascal_(name)] (not a traditional-type Latin name, but the\\\\\\\\n   adjective-turned-name paschalis, meaning 'of Easter' (Pascha)).\\\\\\\\n * Word names come from English vocabulary words. Feminine names of this sortin\\\\\\\\n   more languages than English, and more cultures than Europe alonefrequently\\\\\\\\n   derive from nature, flowers, birds, colours, or gemstones [/wiki/Gemstone].\\\\\\\\n   Examples include Jasmine [/wiki/Jasmine], Lavender [/wiki/Lavender], Dawn\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Dawn], Daisy [/wiki/Asteraceae], Rose [/wiki/Rose], Iris\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Iris_(plant)], Petunia [/wiki/Petunia], Rowan [/wiki/Rowan], Jade\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Jade], and Violet [/wiki/Violet_(plant)]. Male names of this sort are\\\\\\\\n   less commonexamples like Hunter [/wiki/Hunter_(given_name)] and Fischer\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Fischer], or names associated with strong animals, such as Bronco\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Bronco] and Wolf [/wiki/Wolf]. (This is more common in some other\\\\\\\\n   languages, such as Northern Germanic and Turkish).\\\\\\\\n * Trait names most conspicuously include the Christian virtues, mentioned\\\\\\\\n   above, and normally used as feminine names (such as the three Christian\\\\\\\\n   virtues [/wiki/Theological_virtues]Faith [/wiki/Faith_in_Christianity], Hope\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Hope_(virtue)], and Charity [/wiki/Charity_(virtue)]).\\\\\\\\n * Diminutives [/wiki/Diminutive] are sometimes used to distinguish between two\\\\\\\\n   or more people with the same given name. In English, Robert [/wiki/Robert]\\\\\\\\n   may be changed to \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Robbie\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or Thomas changed to \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Tommy\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". In German the names\\\\\\\\n   Hnsel [/wiki/John_(name)#Evolution_of_the_name_John] and Gretel\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Margaret_(name)#Name_Margaret_in_other_languages] (as in the famous\\\\\\\\n   fairy tale [/wiki/Hansel_%26_Gretel]) are the diminutive forms of Johann and\\\\\\\\n   Margarete. Examples: Vicky [/wiki/Victoria_(name)], Cindy\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Cindy_(given_name)], Tommy, Abby [/wiki/Abigail], Allie\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Alison_(name)].\\\\\\\\n * Shortened names (see nickname [/wiki/Nickname]) are generally nicknames of a\\\\\\\\n   longer name, but they are instead given as a person's entire given name. For\\\\\\\\n   example, a man may simply be named \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Jim\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", and it is not short for James\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/James_(name)]. Examples: Beth, Ben, Zach, Tom.\\\\\\\\n * Feminine variations exist for many masculine names, often in multiple forms.\\\\\\\\n   Examples: Charlotte [/wiki/Charlotte_(given_name)], Stephanie\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Stephanie], Victoria [/wiki/Victoria_(name)], Philippa\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Philippa], Jane [/wiki/Jane_(given_name)], Jacqueline\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Jacqueline_(name)], Josephine [/wiki/Josephine_(name)], Danielle\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Danielle], Paula [/wiki/Paula_(given_name)], Pauline\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Pauline_(name)], Patricia [/wiki/Patricia], Francesca\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Francesca].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFrequently, a given name has versions in many languages. For example, the\\\\\\\\nbiblical name Susanna [/wiki/Susanna_(disciple)] also occurs in its original\\\\\\\\nbiblical Hebrew [/wiki/Biblical_Hebrew_language] version, Shoshannah, its\\\\\\\\nSpanish and Portuguese version Susana, its French version, Suzanne, its Polish\\\\\\\\nversion, Zuzanna, or its Hungarian version, Zsuzsanna .\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEAST ASIA\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=6]]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Chinese given names [/wiki/Chinese_given_names]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDespite the uniformity of Chinese surnames [/wiki/Chinese_surname], some Chinese\\\\\\\\ngiven names [/wiki/Chinese_given_name] are fairly original because Chinese\\\\\\\\ncharacters [/wiki/Chinese_character] can be combined extensively. Unlike\\\\\\\\nEuropean languages, with their Biblical and Greco-Roman heritage, the Chinese\\\\\\\\nlanguage [/wiki/Chinese_language] does not have a particular set of words\\\\\\\\nreserved for given names: any combination of Chinese characters can\\\\\\\\ntheoretically be used as a given name. Nonetheless, a number of popular\\\\\\\\ncharacters commonly recur, including \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Strong\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%BC%9F], Wi), \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Learned\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%96%87], Wn), \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Peaceful\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%AE%89], n), and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Beautiful\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%BE%8E], Mi). Despite China's increasing\\\\\\\\nurbanization, several names such as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Pine\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%9D%BE], Sng) or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Plum [/wiki/Plum_tree]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%A2%85], Mi) also still reference nature.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMost Chinese given names are two characters long anddespite the examples\\\\\\\\nabovethe two characters together may mean nothing at all. Instead, they may be\\\\\\\\nselected to include particular sounds, tones [/wiki/Chinese_tones], or radicals\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Radical_(Chinese_characters)]; to balance the Chinese elements\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Five_elements_(China)] of a child's birth chart\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Chinese_astrology]; or to honor a generation poem [/wiki/Generation_poem]\\\\\\\\nhanded down through the family for centuries. Traditionally, it is considered an\\\\\\\\naffront [/wiki/Naming_taboo], not an honor, to have a newborn named after an\\\\\\\\nolder relative and so full names are rarely passed down through a family in the\\\\\\\\nmanner of American English Seniors, Juniors, III, etc. Similarly, it is\\\\\\\\nconsidered disadvantageous for the child to bear a name already made famous by\\\\\\\\nsomeone else through romanizations [/wiki/Romanization_of_Chinese], where a\\\\\\\\ncommon name like Liu Xiang [/wiki/Liu_Xiang_(disambiguation)] may be borne by\\\\\\\\ntens of thousands.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nKorean names [/wiki/Korean_names] and Vietnamese names [/wiki/Vietnamese_names]\\\\\\\\nare often simply conventions derived from Classical Chinese\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Classical_Chinese] counterparts.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMany female Japanese names [/wiki/Japanese_names] end in -ko (\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%AD%90]), usually meaning \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"child\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" on its own.\\\\\\\\nHowever, the character when used in given names can have a feminine (adult)\\\\\\\\nconnotation.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn many Westernised Asian locations, many Asians also have an unofficial or even\\\\\\\\nregistered Western (typically English) given name, in addition to their Asian\\\\\\\\ngiven name. This is also true for Asian students at colleges in countries such\\\\\\\\nas the United States, Canada, and Australia as well as among international\\\\\\\\nbusinesspeople. [citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nGENDER\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=7]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMost names in English are traditionally masculine (Hugo, James, Harold) or\\\\\\\\nfeminine (Daphne, Charlotte, Jane), but there are unisex names\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Unisex_name] as well, such as Jordan [/wiki/Jordan_(name)], Jamie\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Jamie], Jesse [/wiki/Jesse_(given_name)], Morgan\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Morgan_(given_name)], Leslie/Lesley [/wiki/Lesley_(disambiguation)], Joe\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Joseph_(name)]/Jo [/wiki/Jo_(given_name)], Jackie\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Jackie_(given_name)], Pat [/wiki/Pat_(disambiguation)], Dana, Alex, Chris\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Chris]/Kris [/wiki/Kris_(name)], Randy [/wiki/Randy]/Randi [/wiki/Randi],\\\\\\\\nLee [/wiki/Lee_(given_name)], etc. Often, use for one gender is predominant.\\\\\\\\nAlso, a particular spelling is often more common for either men or women, even\\\\\\\\nif the pronunciation is the same.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMany culture groups, past and present, did not or do not gender their names\\\\\\\\nstrongly; thus, many or all of their names are unisex. On the other hand, in\\\\\\\\nmany languages including most Indo-European languages\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Indo-European_languages] (but not English), gender is inherent in the\\\\\\\\ngrammar. Some countries have laws preventing unisex names [/wiki/Unisex_names],\\\\\\\\nrequiring parents to give their children sex-specific names.[29] Names may have\\\\\\\\ndifferent gender connotations from country to country or language to language.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWithin anthroponymic [/wiki/Anthroponymic] classification, names of human males\\\\\\\\nare called andronyms (from Ancient Greek [/wiki/Ancient_Greek]  / man, and\\\\\\\\n [] / name),[30] while names of human females are called gynonyms\\\\\\\\n(from Ancient Greek [/wiki/Ancient_Greek]  / woman, and  [] /\\\\\\\\nname).[31]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPOPULARITY\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=8]]\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/USA_historical_popular_baby_names.svg/250px-USA_historical_popular_baby_names.svg.png]/wiki/File:USA_historical_popular_baby_names.svgMost\\\\\\\\npopular US baby names from 1880 to 2012\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe popularity (frequency) distribution of given names typically follows a power\\\\\\\\nlaw distribution [/wiki/Zipf%E2%80%93Mandelbrot_law].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSince about 1800 in England and Wales and in the U.S., the popularity\\\\\\\\ndistribution of given names has been shifting so that the most popular names are\\\\\\\\nlosing popularity. For example, in England and Wales, the most popular female\\\\\\\\nand male names given to babies born in 1800 were Mary and John, with 24% of\\\\\\\\nfemale babies and 22% of male babies receiving those names, respectively.[32] In\\\\\\\\ncontrast, the corresponding statistics for England and Wales in 1994 were Emily\\\\\\\\nand James, with 3% and 4% of names, respectively. Not only have Mary and John\\\\\\\\ngone out of favour in the English-speaking world, but the overall distribution\\\\\\\\nof names has also changed significantly over the last 100years for females, but\\\\\\\\nnot for males. This has led to an increasing amount of diversity for female\\\\\\\\nnames.[33]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCHOICE OF NAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=9]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEducation, ethnicity, religion, class and political ideology affect parents'\\\\\\\\nchoice of names. Politically conservative parents choose common and traditional\\\\\\\\nnames, while politically liberal parents may choose the names of literary\\\\\\\\ncharacters or other relatively obscure cultural figures.[34] Devout members of\\\\\\\\nreligions often choose names from their religious scriptures. For example, Hindu\\\\\\\\nparents may name a daughter Saanvi [/wiki/Saanvi] after the goddess, Jewish\\\\\\\\nparents may name a boy Isaac [/wiki/Isaac] after one of the earliest ancestral\\\\\\\\nfigures, and Muslim parents may name a boy Mohammed [/wiki/Mohammed_(name)]\\\\\\\\nafter the prophet Mohammed [/wiki/Muhammad].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThere are many tools parents can use to choose names, including books, websites\\\\\\\\nand applications. An example is the Baby Name Game that uses the Elo rating\\\\\\\\nsystem [/wiki/Elo_rating_system] to rank parents preferred names and help them\\\\\\\\nselect one.[35]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nINFLUENCE OF POPULAR CULTURE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=10]]\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/60px-Question_book-new.svg.png]/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg\\\\\\\\nThis section needs additional citations for verification\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability]. Please help improve this article\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Special:EditPage/Given_name] by adding citations to reliable sources\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners] in this section. Unsourced material may\\\\\\\\nbe challenged and removed. (October 2015) (Learn how and when to remove this\\\\\\\\nmessage [/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal])\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPopular culture [/wiki/Popular_culture] appears to have an influence on naming\\\\\\\\ntrends, at least in the United States and United Kingdom. Newly famous\\\\\\\\ncelebrities and public figures may influence the popularity of names. For\\\\\\\\nexample, in 2004, the names \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Keira\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Kiera\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (anglicisation of Irish name\\\\\\\\nCiara) respectively became the 51st and 92nd most popular girls' names in the\\\\\\\\nUK, following the rise in popularity of British actress Keira Knightley\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Keira_Knightley].[36] In 2001, the use of Colby as a boys' name for\\\\\\\\nbabies in the United States jumped from 233rd place to 99th, just after Colby\\\\\\\\nDonaldson [/wiki/Colby_Donaldson] was the runner-up on Survivor: The Australian\\\\\\\\nOutback [/wiki/Survivor:_The_Australian_Outback].[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]] Also, the female name \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Miley\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" which before\\\\\\\\nwas not in the top 1000 was 278th most popular in 2007, following the rise to\\\\\\\\nfame of singer-actress Miley Cyrus [/wiki/Miley_Cyrus] (who was named Destiny at\\\\\\\\nbirth).[37]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Influence_of_TV_series_on_given_names.svg/500px-Influence_of_TV_series_on_given_names.svg.png]/wiki/File:Influence_of_TV_series_on_given_names.svgInfluence\\\\\\\\nof TV series on given names in England and Wales from 1996 to 2021.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCharacters from fiction also seem to influence naming. After the name Kayla\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Kayla_(name)] was used for a character [/wiki/Kayla_Brady] on the\\\\\\\\nAmerican soap opera [/wiki/Soap_opera] Days of Our Lives\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Days_of_Our_Lives], the name's popularity increased greatly. The name\\\\\\\\nTammy [/wiki/Tammy_(given_name)], and the related Tamara\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Tamara_(given_name)] became popular after the movie Tammy and the\\\\\\\\nBachelor [/wiki/Tammy_and_the_Bachelor] came out in 1957. Some names were\\\\\\\\nestablished or spread by being used in literature. Notable examples include\\\\\\\\nPamela [/wiki/Pamela_(name)], invented by Sir Philip Sidney\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Philip_Sidney] for a pivotal character in his epic prose work, The\\\\\\\\nCountess of Pembroke's Arcadia [/wiki/The_Countess_of_Pembroke%27s_Arcadia];\\\\\\\\nJessica [/wiki/Jessica_(given_name)], created by William Shakespeare in his play\\\\\\\\nThe Merchant of Venice [/wiki/The_Merchant_of_Venice]; Vanessa\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Vanessa_(name)], created by Jonathan Swift [/wiki/Jonathan_Swift]; Fiona\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Fiona], a character from James Macpherson [/wiki/James_Macpherson]'s\\\\\\\\nspurious cycle of Ossian [/wiki/Ossian] poems; Wendy [/wiki/Wendy], an obscure\\\\\\\\nname popularised by J. M. Barrie [/wiki/J._M._Barrie] in his play Peter Pan, or\\\\\\\\nThe Boy Who Wouldn't Grow Up\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Peter_Pan,_or_The_Boy_Who_Wouldn%27t_Grow_Up]; and Madison\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Madison_(name)], a character from the movie Splash [/wiki/Splash_(film)].\\\\\\\\nLara [/wiki/Lara_(name)] and Larissa [/wiki/Larissa_(given_name)] were rare in\\\\\\\\nAmerica before the appearance of Doctor Zhivago\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Doctor_Zhivago_(1965_film)], and have become fairly common since.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSongs can influence the naming of children. Jude jumped from 814th most popular\\\\\\\\nmale name in 1968 to 668th in 1969, following the release of the Beatles\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/The_Beatles]' \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Hey Jude [/wiki/Hey_Jude]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". Similarly, Layla [/wiki/Layla]\\\\\\\\ncharted as 969th most popular in 1972 after the Eric Clapton\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Eric_Clapton] song. It had not been in the top 1,000 before.[37] Kayleigh\\\\\\\\nbecame a particularly popular name in the United Kingdom following the release\\\\\\\\nof a song by the British rock group Marillion [/wiki/Marillion]. Government\\\\\\\\nstatistics in 2005 revealed that 96% of Kayleighs were born after 1985, the year\\\\\\\\nin which Marillion released \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Kayleigh [/wiki/Kayleigh]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". [citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPopular culture figures need not be admirable in order to influence naming\\\\\\\\ntrends. For example, Peyton came into the top 1000 as a female given name for\\\\\\\\nbabies in the United States for the first time in 1992 (at #583), immediately\\\\\\\\nafter it was featured as the name of an evil nanny in the film The Hand That\\\\\\\\nRocks the Cradle [/wiki/The_Hand_That_Rocks_the_Cradle_(1992_film)].[37] On the\\\\\\\\nother hand, historical events can influence child-naming. For example, the given\\\\\\\\nname Adolf [/wiki/Adolf] has fallen out of use since the end of World War II\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/World_War_II] in 1945.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn contrast with this anecdotal evidence, a comprehensive study of Norwegian\\\\\\\\nfirst name datasets[38] shows that the main factors that govern first name\\\\\\\\ndynamics are endogenous [/wiki/Endogenous]. Monitoring the popularity of 1,000\\\\\\\\nnames over 130 years, the authors have identified only five cases of exogenous\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Exogenous] effects, three of them are connected to the names given to the\\\\\\\\nbabies of the Norwegian royal family.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n20TH CENTURY AFRICAN-AMERICAN NAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=11]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSince the civil rights movement of 19501970, African-American names\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/African-American_names] given to children have strongly mirrored\\\\\\\\nsociopolitical movements and philosophies in the African-American community.\\\\\\\\nSince the 1970s neologistic (creative, inventive) practices have become\\\\\\\\nincreasingly common and the subject of academic study.[39]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSEE ALSO\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=12]]\\\\\\\\n * name  given name order is used only in informal or\\\\\\\\n    traditional contexts. The official naming order in Austria [/wiki/Austria]\\\\\\\\n    and Bavaria [/wiki/Bavaria] is given name  family name.\\\\\\\\n 2. ^ Protesting Swedish naming laws, in 1996, two parents attempted to name\\\\\\\\n    their child Brfxxccxxmnpcccclllmmnprxvclmnckssqlbb11116\\\\\\\\n    [/wiki/Naming_law_in_Sweden#Protest_names], stating that it was \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"a pregnant,\\\\\\\\n    expressionistic development that we see as an artistic creation\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[6]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nREFERENCES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=14]]\\\\\\\\n 1.  ^ a b c Grigg, John [/wiki/John_Grigg] (2 November 1991). \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"The Times\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n     [/wiki/The_Times]. In the last century and well into the present one,\\\\\\\\n     grown-up British people, with rare exceptions, addressed each other by\\\\\\\\n     their surnames. What we now call first names (then Christian names) were\\\\\\\\n     very little used outside the family. Men who became friends would drop the\\\\\\\\n     Mr and use their bare surnames as a mark of intimacy: e.g. Holmes\\\\\\\\n     [/wiki/Sherlock_Holmes] and Watson [/wiki/Dr._Watson]. First names were\\\\\\\\n     only generally used for, and among, children. Today we have gone to the\\\\\\\\n     other extreme. People tend to be on first-name terms from the moment of\\\\\\\\n     introduction, and surnames are often hardly mentioned. Moreover, first\\\\\\\\n     names are relentlessly abbreviated, particularly in the media: Susan\\\\\\\\n     becomes Sue [/wiki/Sue_Lawley], Terrence Terry [/wiki/Terry_Wogan] and\\\\\\\\n     Robert Bob [/wiki/Bob_Holness] not only to friends and relations, but to\\\\\\\\n     millions who know these people only as faces and/or voices. quoted in\\\\\\\\n     Burchfield, R. W. [/wiki/Robert_Burchfield] (1996). The New Fowler's Modern\\\\\\\\n     English Usage [https://archive.org/details/newfowlersmodern00fowl]\\\\\\\\n     (3rded.). Oxford University Press. p.512. semi-protected\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/1b/Semi-protection-shackle.svg/20px-Semi-protection-shackle.svg.png]/wiki/Wikipedia:Protection_policy#semi\\\\\\\\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nInformation page on Wikipedia categories\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFor guidelines on the use of categories on Wikipedia, see\\\\\\\\nWikipedia:Categorization [/wiki/Wikipedia:Categorization]. For a basic readers'\\\\\\\\nguide, see Help:Categories [/wiki/Help:Categories]. For quick answers, see the\\\\\\\\nreaders' FAQ [/wiki/Wikipedia:FAQ/Categories] or the editors' FAQ\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:FAQ/Categorization] on categories. For a list of categories,\\\\\\\\nsee Special:Categories [/wiki/Special:Categories].\\\\\\\\nThis page describes editing with the source editor. See Help:VisualEditor\\\\\\\\nEditing categories [/wiki/Help:VisualEditor#Editing_categories] for\\\\\\\\nVisualEditor [/wiki/Wikipedia:VisualEditor].\\\\\\\\nWikipedia information page\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/1d/Information_icon4.svg/40px-Information_icon4.svg.png]\\\\\\\\nThis is an information page\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Project_namespace#How-to_and_information_pages].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIt is not an encyclopedic article [/wiki/Wikipedia:What_is_an_article%3F], nor\\\\\\\\none of Wikipedia's policies or guidelines\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Policies_and_guidelines]; rather, its purpose is to explain\\\\\\\\ncertain aspects of Wikipedia's norms, customs, technicalities, or practices. It\\\\\\\\nmay reflect differing levels of consensus [/wiki/Wikipedia:Consensus] and\\\\\\\\nvetting [/wiki/Wikipedia:Consensus#Achieving_consensus].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcut
