For other uses, see Last Name (disambiguation)\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Last_Name_(disambiguation)].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Family name\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" redirects here. For other uses, see Family Name (disambiguation)\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Family_Name_(disambiguation)].\\\\\\\\nNot to be confused with Suriname [/wiki/Suriname].\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/60px-Question_book-new.svg.png]/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg\\\\\\\\nThis article needs additional citations for verification\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability]. Please help improve this article\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Special:EditPage/Surname] by adding citations to reliable sources\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners]. Unsourced material may be challenged and\\\\\\\\nremoved.\\\\\\\\nFind sources:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Surname\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n[https://www.google.com/search?as_eq=wikipedia&q=%22Surname%22]news\\\\\\\\n[https://www.google.com/search?tbm=nws&q=%22Surname%22+-wikipedia&tbs=ar:1]\\\\\\\\nnewspapers [https://www.google.com/search?&q=%22Surname%22&tbs=bkt:s&tbm=bks]\\\\\\\\nbooks [https://www.google.com/search?tbs=bks:1&q=%22Surname%22+-wikipedia]\\\\\\\\nscholar [https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22Surname%22] JSTOR\\\\\\\\n[https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Surname%22&acc=on&wc=on]\\\\\\\\n(February 2023) (Learn how and when to remove this message\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal])\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/FML_names-2.png/330px-FML_names-2.png]/wiki/File:FML_names-2.pngFirst/given/forename,\\\\\\\\nmiddle, and last/family/surname with John Fitzgerald Kennedy\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/John_F._Kennedy] as example. This shows a structure typical for\\\\\\\\nAnglophonic cultures (and some others). Other cultures use other structures for\\\\\\\\nfull names.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA surname, family name, or last name is the mostly hereditary portion of one's\\\\\\\\npersonal name [/wiki/Personal_name] that indicates one's family.[1][2] It is\\\\\\\\ntypically combined with a given name [/wiki/Given_name] to form the full name\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Full_name] of a person, although several given names and surnames are\\\\\\\\npossible in the full name. In modern times most surnames are hereditary,\\\\\\\\nalthough in most countries a person has a right to change their name\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Name_change].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDepending on culture, the surname may be placed either at the start of a\\\\\\\\nperson's name, or at the end. The number of surnames given to an individual also\\\\\\\\nvaries: in most cases it is just one, but in Portuguese-speaking countries and\\\\\\\\nmany Spanish-speaking countries, two surnames (one inherited from the mother and\\\\\\\\nanother from the father) are used for legal purposes. Depending on culture, not\\\\\\\\nall members of a family unit are required to have identical surnames. In some\\\\\\\\ncountries, surnames are modified depending on gender and family membership\\\\\\\\nstatus of a person. Compound surnames can be composed of separate names.[3]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe use of names has been documented in even the oldest historical records.\\\\\\\\nExamples of surnames are documented in the 11th century by the barons\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Baron] in England. English surnames began to be formed with reference to\\\\\\\\na certain aspect of that individual, such as their trade, father's name,\\\\\\\\nlocation of birth, or physical features, and were not necessarily inherited. By\\\\\\\\n1400 most English families, and those from Lowland Scotland, had adopted the use\\\\\\\\nof hereditary surnames.[4]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe study of proper names (in family names, personal names, or places) is called\\\\\\\\nonomastics [/wiki/Onomastics].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nHISTORY\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=1]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nORIGIN\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=2]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWhile the use of given names to identify individuals is attested in the oldest\\\\\\\\nhistorical records, the advent of surnames is relatively recent.[5] Many\\\\\\\\ncultures have used and continue to use additional descriptive terms in\\\\\\\\nidentifying individuals. These terms may indicate personal attributes, location\\\\\\\\nof origin, occupation, parentage, patronage, adoption, or clan affiliation.[6]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn China, according to legend, family names started with Emperor Fu Xi\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Fuxi] in 2000 BC.[7] His administration standardised the naming system to\\\\\\\\nfacilitate census-taking, and the use of census information. Originally, Chinese\\\\\\\\nsurnames [/wiki/Chinese_surname] were derived matrilineally,[8] although by the\\\\\\\\ntime of the Shang dynasty [/wiki/Shang_dynasty] (1600 to 1046 BC) they had\\\\\\\\nbecome patrilineal.[8][9] Chinese women do not change their names upon\\\\\\\\nmarriage.[10] In China, surnames have been the norm since at least the 2nd\\\\\\\\ncentury BC.[11]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn the early Islamic [/wiki/Islamic] period (640900 AD) and the Arab world\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Arab_world], the use of patronymics [/wiki/Patronymics] is well attested.\\\\\\\\nThe famous scholar Rhazes [/wiki/Rhazes] (c.865925 AD) is referred to as\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"al-Razi\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (lit. the one from Ray) due to his origins from the city of Ray\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Ray,_Iran], Iran. In the Levant [/wiki/Levant], surnames were in use as\\\\\\\\nearly as the High Middle Ages [/wiki/High_Middle_Ages] and it was common for\\\\\\\\npeople to derive their surname from a distant ancestor, and historically the\\\\\\\\nsurname would be often preceded with 'ibn' or 'son of'. Arab family names often\\\\\\\\ndenote either one's tribe [/wiki/Tribe], profession [/wiki/Profession], a famous\\\\\\\\nancestor, or the place of origin; but they were not universal. For example,\\\\\\\\nHunayn ibn Ishaq [/wiki/Hunayn_ibn_Ishaq] (fl. 850 AD) was known by the nisbah\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"al-'Ibadi\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", a federation of Arab Christian tribes that lived in Mesopotamia\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Mesopotamia] prior to the advent of Islam [/wiki/Islam].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Ancient Greece, as far back as the Archaic Period [/wiki/Archaic_Greece] clan\\\\\\\\nnames and patronymics [/wiki/Patronymic] (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"son of\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") were also common, as in\\\\\\\\nAristides [/wiki/Aristides] as   a genitive singular form meaning son\\\\\\\\nof Lysimachus. For example, Alexander the Great [/wiki/Alexander_the_Great] was\\\\\\\\nknown as Heracleides [/wiki/Heracleidae], as a supposed descendant of Heracles\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Heracles], and by the dynastic name Karanos/Caranus\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Caranus_of_Macedon], which referred to the founder of the dynasty to\\\\\\\\nwhich he belonged [/wiki/Argead_dynasty]. These patronymics are already attested\\\\\\\\nfor many characters in the works of Homer [/wiki/Homer]. At other times formal\\\\\\\\nidentification commonly included the place of origin.[12]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOver the course of the Roman Republic and the later Empire, naming conventions\\\\\\\\nwent through multiple changes. (See Roman naming conventions\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Roman_naming_conventions].) The nomen [/wiki/Nomen_gentilicium], the name\\\\\\\\nof the gens [/wiki/Gens] (tribe) inherited patrilineally, is thought to have\\\\\\\\nalready been in use by 650 BC.[13] The nomen was to identify group kinship,\\\\\\\\nwhile the praenomen [/wiki/Praenomen] (forename; plural praenomina) was used to\\\\\\\\ndistinguish individuals within the group. Female praenomina were less common, as\\\\\\\\nwomen had reduced public influence, and were commonly known by the feminine form\\\\\\\\nof the nomen alone.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMEDIEVAL ERA AND BEYOND\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=3]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLater with the gradual influence of Greek and Christian culture\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Christian_culture] throughout the Empire, Christian religious names were\\\\\\\\nsometimes put in front of traditional cognomina, but eventually people reverted\\\\\\\\nto single names.[14] By the time of the fall of the Western Roman Empire in the\\\\\\\\n5th century, family names were uncommon in the Eastern Roman Empire\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Eastern_Roman_Empire]. In Western Europe, where Germanic culture\\\\\\\\ndominated the aristocracy, family names were almost non-existent. They would not\\\\\\\\nsignificantly reappear again in Eastern Roman society until the 10th century,\\\\\\\\napparently influenced by the familial affiliations of the Armenian military\\\\\\\\naristocracy.[14] The practice of using family names spread through the Eastern\\\\\\\\nRoman Empire, however it was not until the 11th century that surnames came to be\\\\\\\\nused in West Europe.[15]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMedieval Spain used a patronymic system. For example, lvaro, a son of Rodrigo,\\\\\\\\nwould be named lvaro Rodrguez. His son, Juan, would not be named Juan\\\\\\\\nRodrguez, but Juan lvarez. Over time, many of these patronymics became family\\\\\\\\nnames, and they are some of the most common names in the Spanish-speaking world\\\\\\\\ntoday. Other sources of surnames are personal appearance or habit, e.g. Delgado\\\\\\\\n(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"thin\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") and Moreno (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"dark\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"); geographic location or ethnicity, e.g. Alemn\\\\\\\\n(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"German\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"); and occupations, e.g. Molinero (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"miller\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), Zapatero (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"shoe-maker\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\")\\\\\\\\nand Guerrero (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"warrior\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), although occupational names are much more often found\\\\\\\\nin a shortened form referring to the trade itself, e.g. Molina (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"mill\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), Guerra\\\\\\\\n(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"war\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), or Zapata (archaic form of zapato, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"shoe\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\").[16]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn England the introduction of family names is generally attributed to the\\\\\\\\npreparation of the Domesday Book [/wiki/Domesday_Book] in 1086, following the\\\\\\\\nNorman Conquest [/wiki/Norman_Conquest]. Evidence indicates that surnames were\\\\\\\\nfirst adopted among the feudal nobility and gentry, and slowly spread to other\\\\\\\\nparts of society. Some of the early Norman nobility who arrived in England\\\\\\\\nduring the Norman conquest differentiated themselves by affixing 'de' (of)\\\\\\\\nbefore the name of their village in France. This is what is known as a\\\\\\\\nterritorial surname, a consequence of feudal landownership. By the 14th century,\\\\\\\\nmost English [/wiki/English_surnames] and most Scottish\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Scottish_surnames] people used surnames and in Wales following\\\\\\\\nunification under Henry VIII in 1536.[17]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA four-year study led by the University of the West of England\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/University_of_the_West_of_England], which concluded in 2016, analysed\\\\\\\\nsources dating from the 11th to the 19th century to explain the origins of the\\\\\\\\nsurnames in the British Isles [/wiki/British_Isles].[18] The study found that\\\\\\\\nover 90% of the 45,602 surnames in the dictionary are native to Britain and\\\\\\\\nIreland, with the most common in the UK being Smith [/wiki/Smith_(surname)],\\\\\\\\nJones [/wiki/Jones_(surname)], Williams [/wiki/Williams_(surname)], Brown\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Brown_(surname)], Taylor [/wiki/Taylor_(surname)], Davies [/wiki/Davies],\\\\\\\\nand Wilson [/wiki/Wilson_(name)].[19] The findings have been published in the\\\\\\\\nOxford English Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland, with project\\\\\\\\nleader Richard Coates calling the study \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"more detailed and accurate\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" than those\\\\\\\\nbefore.[18] He elaborated on the origins: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Some surnames have origins that are\\\\\\\\noccupational  obvious examples are Smith and Baker. Other names can be linked\\\\\\\\nto a place [/wiki/Toponymic_surname], for example, Hill or Green, which relates\\\\\\\\nto a village green [/wiki/Village_green]. Surnames that are 'patronymic' are\\\\\\\\nthose which originally enshrined the father's name  such as Jackson\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Jackson_(name)], or Jenkinson [/wiki/Jenkinson]. There are also names\\\\\\\\nwhere the origin describes the original bearer such as Brown, Short\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Short_stature], or Thin  though Short may in fact be an ironic\\\\\\\\n'nickname' surname for a tall person.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"[18]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn the modern era, governments have enacted laws to require people to adopt\\\\\\\\nsurnames. This served the purpose of uniquely identifying subjects for taxation\\\\\\\\npurposes or for inheritance.[20] In the late Middle Ages [/wiki/Middle_Ages] in\\\\\\\\nEngland, mandatory surnames were resisted as they were associated with\\\\\\\\ntaxes.[21]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMODERN ERA\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=4]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDuring the modern era many cultures around the world adopted family names,\\\\\\\\nparticularly for administrative reasons, especially during the age of European\\\\\\\\nexpansion and particularly since 1600. The Napoleonic Code, adopted in various\\\\\\\\nparts of Europe, stipulated that people should be known by both their given\\\\\\\\nname(s) and a family name that would not change across generations. Other\\\\\\\\nnotable examples include the Netherlands (17951811), Japan (1870s), Thailand\\\\\\\\n(1920), and Turkey (1934). The structure of the Japanese name\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Japanese_name] was formalized by the government as family name + given\\\\\\\\nname in 1868.[22]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Breslau Prussia enacted the Hoym Ordinance in 1790, mandating the adoption of\\\\\\\\nJewish surnames.[23][24] Napoleon also insisted on Jews adopting fixed names in\\\\\\\\na decree issued in 1808.[25]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nNames can sometimes be changed to protect individual privacy (such as in witness\\\\\\\\nprotection [/wiki/Witness_protection]), or in cases where groups of people are\\\\\\\\nescaping persecution.[26] After arriving in the United States, European Jews who\\\\\\\\nfled Nazi persecution sometimes anglicized [/wiki/Anglicization] their surnames\\\\\\\\nto avoid discrimination.[27] Governments can also forcibly change people's\\\\\\\\nnames, as when the National Socialist [/wiki/National_Socialist] government of\\\\\\\\nGermany assigned German names to European people in the territories they\\\\\\\\nconquered.[28] In the 1980s, the People's Republic of Bulgaria\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/People%27s_Republic_of_Bulgaria] forcibly changed the first and last\\\\\\\\nnames of its Turkish citizens [/wiki/Turks_in_Bulgaria] to Bulgarian names.[29]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nORIGINS OF PARTICULAR SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=5]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPATRONYMIC AND MATRONYMIC SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=6]]\\\\\\\\nMain articles: Patronymic surname [/wiki/Patronymic_surname] and Matronymic\\\\\\\\nsurname [/wiki/Matronymic_surname]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Icelandic name [/wiki/Icelandic_name], Habesha name\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Habesha_name], Arabic name [/wiki/Arabic_name], and Hebrew name\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Hebrew_name]\\\\\\\\nSee also the categories Patronymic surnames [/wiki/Category:Patronymic_surnames]\\\\\\\\nand Matronymic surnames [/wiki/Category:Matronymic_surnames]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThese are the oldest and most common type of surname.[30] They may be a first\\\\\\\\nname such as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Wilhelm\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", a patronymic [/wiki/Patronymic] such as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Andersen\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Andersen]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", a matronymic [/wiki/Matronymic] such as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Beaton\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Beaton_(surname)]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", or a clan name such as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"O'Brien\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/O%27Brien_dynasty]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". Multiple surnames may be derived from a single given\\\\\\\\nname: e.g. there are thought to be over 90 Italian surnames based on the given\\\\\\\\nname \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Giovanni [/wiki/Giovanni_(name)]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[30]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Icelandic_Patronyms.svg/250px-Icelandic_Patronyms.svg.png]/wiki/File:Icelandic_Patronyms.svgA\\\\\\\\nfamily tree showing the Icelandic patronymic naming system\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEXAMPLES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=7]]\\\\\\\\n * Patronal from patronage (Hickman meaning Hick's man, where Hick is a pet form\\\\\\\\n   of the name Richard) or strong ties of religion Kilpatrick (follower of\\\\\\\\n   Patrick [/wiki/Patrick_(given_name)]) or Kilbride (follower of Saint Brigid\\\\\\\\n   of Kildare [/wiki/Brigid_of_Kildare]).[31]\\\\\\\\n * Patronymics [/wiki/Patronymic], matronymics [/wiki/Matronymic] or ancestral,\\\\\\\\n   often from a person's given name. e.g., from male name: Richardson\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Richardson_(surname)], Stephenson [/wiki/Stephenson], Jones\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Jones_(surname)] (Welsh for Johnson), Williams\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Williams_(surname)], Jackson [/wiki/Jackson_(name)], Wilson\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wilson_(surname)], Thompson [/wiki/Thompson_(surname)], Benson\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Benson_(surname)], Johnson [/wiki/Johnson_(surname)], Harris\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Harris_(surname)], Evans [/wiki/Evans_(surname)], Simpson\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Simpson_(surname)], Willis [/wiki/Willis_(surname)], Davies\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Davies], Reynolds [/wiki/Reynolds_(surname)], Adams\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Adams_(surname)], Dawson [/wiki/Dawson_(surname)], Lewis\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Lewis_(surname)], Rogers [/wiki/Rogers_(surname)], Murphy\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Murphy], Morrow [/wiki/Morrow_(surname)], Nicholson\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Nicholson_(surname)], Robinson [/wiki/Robinson_(name)], Powell\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Powell_(surname)], Ferguson [/wiki/Ferguson_(name)], Davis\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Davis_(surname)], Edwards [/wiki/Edwards_(surname)], Hudson\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Hudson_(surname)], Roberts [/wiki/Roberts_(surname)], Harrison\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Harrison_(name)], Watson [/wiki/Watson_(surname)], or female names\\\\\\\\n   Molson (from Moll for Mary), Madison [/wiki/Madison_(name)] (from Maud),\\\\\\\\n   Emmott (from Emma), Marriott (from Mary) or from a clan name (for those of\\\\\\\\n   Scottish origin, e.g., MacDonald [/wiki/Macdonald_(name)], Forbes\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Clan_Forbes], Henderson [/wiki/Henderson_(surname)], Armstrong\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Armstrong_(surname)], Grant [/wiki/Grant_(surname)], Cameron\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Cameron_(surname)], Stewart [/wiki/Stewart_(name)], Douglas\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Douglas_(surname)], Crawford [/wiki/Crawford_(name)], Campbell\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Campbell_(surname)], Hunter [/wiki/Hunter_(name)]) with \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mac\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" Gaelic\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Goidelic_languages] for son.[32]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCOGNOMINAL SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=8]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThis is the broadest class of surnames, originating from nicknames,[33]\\\\\\\\nencompassing many types of origin. These include names based on appearance such\\\\\\\\nas \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Schwartzkopf\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Short\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", and possibly \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Caesar\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",[30] and names based on\\\\\\\\ntemperament and personality such as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Daft\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Gutman\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Maiden\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", which,\\\\\\\\naccording to a number of sources, was an English nickname meaning\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"effeminate\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[30][34]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA group of nicknames look like occupational ones: King [/wiki/King_(surname)],\\\\\\\\nBishop [/wiki/Bishop_(surname)], Abbot [/wiki/Abbot_(surname)], Sheriff\\\\\\\\n[/w/index.php?title=Sheriff_(surname)&action=edit&redlink=1], Knight\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Knight_(surname)], etc. but it is rather unlikely that a person with\\\\\\\\nsurname King was a king or descended from a king. Bernard Deacon\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Bernard_Deacon_(linguist)] suggests that the first nickname/surname\\\\\\\\nbearer may have acted like a king or bishop, or was as corpulent as a bishop.\\\\\\\\netc.[33]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA considerable group of surname-producing nicknames may be found among\\\\\\\\nethnonymic surnames [/wiki/Ethnonymic_surname].[35][36]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nORNAMENTAL/ARTIFICIAL SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=9]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOrnamental surnames (also known as artificial surnames[37][38]) are not specific\\\\\\\\nto any attribute (place, parentage, occupation, caste) of the first person to\\\\\\\\nacquire the name. They were generally acquired later in history and generally\\\\\\\\nwhen those without surnames needed them. In 1526, King Frederik I of\\\\\\\\nDenmark-Norway [/wiki/Frederick_I_of_Denmark] ordered that noble families must\\\\\\\\ntake up fixed surnames, and many of them took as their name some element of\\\\\\\\ntheir coat of arms; for example, the Rosenkrantz\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Rosenkrantz_(noble_family)] (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"rose wreath\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") family took their surname\\\\\\\\nfrom a wreath of roses forming the torse of their arms,[39] and the\\\\\\\\nGyldenstierne [/wiki/Gyldenstierne_(noble_family)] (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"golden star\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") family took\\\\\\\\ntheirs from a 7-pointed gold star on their shield.[40] Subsequently, many\\\\\\\\nmiddle-class Scandinavian families desired names similar to those of the nobles\\\\\\\\nand adopted \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"ornamental\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" surnames as well.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMost other naming traditions refer to them as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"acquired\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". They might be given to\\\\\\\\npeople newly immigrated, conquered, or converted, as well as those with unknown\\\\\\\\nparentage, formerly enslaved, or from parentage without a surname\\\\\\\\ntradition.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOrnamental surnames are more common in communities that adopted (or were forced\\\\\\\\nto adopt) surnames in the 18th and 19th centuries.[41] They occur commonly in\\\\\\\\nScandinavia, and among Sinti and Roma [/wiki/Sinti_and_Roma] and Eastern\\\\\\\\nAshkenazi [/wiki/Ashkenazi] Jews in Germany and Austria.[30]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nACQUIRED/ASSIGNED SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=10]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDuring the era of the Trans-Atlantic slave trade\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Trans-Atlantic_slave_trade] many Africans were given new names by their\\\\\\\\nmasters. Many of the family names of many African-Americans have their origins\\\\\\\\nin slavery (i.e. slave name [/wiki/Slave_name]). Some freed slaves later created\\\\\\\\nfamily names themselves.[42]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAnother category of acquired names is foundlings [/wiki/Child_abandonment]'\\\\\\\\nnames. Historically, children born to unwed parents or extremely poor parents\\\\\\\\nwould be abandoned in a public place or anonymously placed in a foundling wheel\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Baby_hatch#History]. Such abandoned children might be claimed and named\\\\\\\\nby religious figures, the community leaders, or adoptive parents. Some such\\\\\\\\nchildren were given surnames that reflected their condition, like (Italian)\\\\\\\\nEsposito [/wiki/Esposito], Innocenti [/wiki/Innocenti_(surname)], Della\\\\\\\\nCasagrande [/wiki/Casagrande], Trovato [/wiki/Trovato], Abbandonata, or (Dutch)\\\\\\\\nVondeling, Verlaeten, Bijstand. Other children were named for the street/place\\\\\\\\nthey were found (Union, Liquorpond (street), di Palermo, Baan, Bijdam, van den\\\\\\\\nEyngel (shop name), van der Stoep\\\\\\\\n[/w/index.php?title=Van_der_Stoep_(surname)&action=edit&redlink=1], von Trapp),\\\\\\\\nthe date they were found (Monday [/wiki/Monday_(surname)], Septembre, Spring, di\\\\\\\\nGennaio), or festival/feast day they found or christened (Easter, SanJos). Some\\\\\\\\nfoundlings were given the name of whoever found them.[43][44][45]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOCCUPATIONAL SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=11]]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Category:Occupational surnames [/wiki/Category:Occupational_surnames]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOccupational [/wiki/Vocation] names include Smith [/wiki/Smith_(surname)],\\\\\\\\nMiller [/wiki/Miller_(name)], Farmer [/wiki/Farmer_(surname)], Thatcher\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Thatcher_(disambiguation)#Surname], Shepherd [/wiki/Shepherd_(surname)],\\\\\\\\nPotter [/wiki/Potter_(surname)], and so on, and analogous names in many other\\\\\\\\nlanguages; see, for example, various surnames associated with the occupation of\\\\\\\\nsmith [/wiki/Template:Smith-surname]. There are also more complicated names\\\\\\\\nbased on occupational titles. In England it was common for servants to take a\\\\\\\\nmodified version of their employer's occupation or first name as their last\\\\\\\\nname,[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]] adding the letter s to\\\\\\\\nthe word, although this formation could also be a patronymic [/wiki/Patronymic].\\\\\\\\nFor instance, the surname Vickers [/wiki/Vickers_(surname)] is thought to have\\\\\\\\narisen as an occupational name adopted by the servant of a vicar,[46] while\\\\\\\\nRoberts [/wiki/Roberts_(surname)] could have been adopted by either the son or\\\\\\\\nthe servant of a man named Robert. A subset of occupational names in English are\\\\\\\\nnames thought to be derived from the medieval mystery plays\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Mystery_play#English_mystery_plays]. The participants would often play\\\\\\\\nthe same roles for life, passing the part down to their oldest sons. Names\\\\\\\\nderived from this may include King [/wiki/King_(surname)], Lord\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Lord_(surname)] and Virgin.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]] A Dictionary of English Surnames says that\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"surnames of office, such as Abbot [/wiki/Abbot_(surname)], Bishop\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Bishop_(surname)], Cardinal [/wiki/Cardinal_(surname)] and King, are\\\\\\\\noften nicknames\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[46] The original meaning of names based on medieval\\\\\\\\noccupations may no longer be obvious in modern English.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nTOPONYMIC SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=12]]\\\\\\\\nMain article: Toponymic surname [/wiki/Toponymic_surname]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLocation (toponymic, habitation) names derive from the inhabited location\\\\\\\\nassociated with the person given that name. Such locations can be any type of\\\\\\\\nsettlement, such as homesteads, farms, enclosures, villages, hamlets,\\\\\\\\nstrongholds, or cottages. One element of a habitation name may describe the type\\\\\\\\nof settlement. Examples of Old English [/wiki/Old_English] elements are\\\\\\\\nfrequently found in the second element of habitational names. The habitative\\\\\\\\nelements in such names can differ in meaning, according to different periods,\\\\\\\\ndifferent locations, or with being used with certain other elements. For\\\\\\\\nexample, the Old English element tn may have originally meant \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"enclosure\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" in\\\\\\\\none name, but can have meant \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"farmstead\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"village\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"manor\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"estate\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" in\\\\\\\\nother names.[47]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLocation names, or habitation names, may be as generic as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Monte\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (Portuguese\\\\\\\\nfor \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"mountain\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Grski\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (Polish for \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"hill\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Pitt\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (variant of \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"pit\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), but\\\\\\\\nmay also refer to specific locations. \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Washington\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", for instance, is thought to\\\\\\\\nmean \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"the homestead of the family of Wassa\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",[34] while \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Lucci\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"resident\\\\\\\\nof Lucca [/wiki/Lucca]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[30] Although some surnames, such as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"London\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Lisboa\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\nor \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Biaystok\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" are derived from large cities, more people reflect the names of\\\\\\\\nsmaller communities, as in  Creachmhaoil [/wiki/%C3%93_Creachmhaoil], derived\\\\\\\\nfrom a village in County Galway [/wiki/County_Galway]. This is thought to be due\\\\\\\\nto the tendency in Europe during the Middle Ages for migration to chiefly be\\\\\\\\nfrom smaller communities to the cities and the need for new arrivals to choose a\\\\\\\\ndefining surname.[34][41]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Portuguese-speaking countries [/wiki/Portuguese-speaking_countries], it is\\\\\\\\nuncommon, but not unprecedented, to find surnames derived from names of\\\\\\\\ncountries, such as Portugal, Frana, Brasil, Holanda. Surnames derived from\\\\\\\\ncountry names are also found in English, such as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"England\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Wales\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Spain\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSome Japanese surnames [/wiki/Japanese_name] derive from geographical features;\\\\\\\\nfor example, Ishikawa [/wiki/Ishikawa_(surname)] () means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"stone river\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (and\\\\\\\\nis also the name of one of Japan's prefectures [/wiki/Ishikawa_Prefecture]),\\\\\\\\nYamamoto [/wiki/Yamamoto] () means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"the base of the mountain\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", and Inoue\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Inoue] () means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"above the well\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nArabic names sometimes contain surnames that denote the city of origin. For\\\\\\\\nexample, in cases of Saddam Hussein [/wiki/Saddam_Hussein] al Tikriti,[48]\\\\\\\\nmeaning Saddam Hussein originated from Tikrit [/wiki/Tikrit], a city in Iraq\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Iraq]. This component of the name is called a nisbah\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Nisbat_(onomastics)].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEXAMPLES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=13]]\\\\\\\\n * Estate names For those descended from land-owners, the name of their\\\\\\\\n   holdings, castle, manor or estate, e.g. Ernle [/wiki/Ernle], Windsor\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/House_of_Windsor], Staunton [/wiki/Staunton_(surname)]\\\\\\\\n * Habitation (place) names e.g., Burton [/wiki/Burton_(name)], Flint\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Flint_(surname)], Hamilton [/wiki/Hamilton_(surname_and_title)],\\\\\\\\n   London [/wiki/London_(name)], Laughton [/wiki/Laughton_(surname)], Leighton\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Leighton_(surname)], Murray [/wiki/Murray_(surname)], Sutton\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Sutton_(surname)], Tremblay [/wiki/Tremblay_(surname)]\\\\\\\\n * Topographic surnames [/wiki/Topographic_surname] (geographical features)\\\\\\\\n   e.g., Bridge [/wiki/Bridge_(surname)] or Bridges [/wiki/Bridges_(surname)],\\\\\\\\n   Brook [/wiki/Brook_(surname)] or Brooks [/wiki/Brooks_(surname)], Bush\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Bush_(surname)], Camp [/wiki/Camp_(surname)], Hill\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Hill_(surname)], Lake [/wiki/Lake_(surname)], Lee\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Lee_(English_name)] or Leigh [/wiki/Leigh_(surname)], Wood\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wood_(surname)], Grove [/wiki/Grove_(surname)], Holmes\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Holmes_(surname)], Forest [/wiki/Forest_(name)], Underwood\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Underwood_(surname)], Hall [/wiki/Hall_(surname)], Field\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Field_(surname)], Stone [/wiki/Stone_(surname)], Morley\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Morley_(name)], Moore [/wiki/Moore_(surname)], Perry\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Perry_(surname)]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOTHER\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=14]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe meanings of some names are unknown or unclear. The most common European name\\\\\\\\nin this category may be the Irish name Ryan [/wiki/Ryan_(surname)], which means\\\\\\\\n'little king' in Irish.[34][46] Also, Celtic origin of the name Arthur, meaning\\\\\\\\n'bear [/wiki/Artur]'. Other surnames may have arisen from more than one source:\\\\\\\\nthe name De Luca [/wiki/DeLuca], for instance, likely arose either in or near\\\\\\\\nLucania or in the family of someone named Lucas or Lucius;[30] in some\\\\\\\\ninstances, however, the name may have arisen from Lucca, with the spelling and\\\\\\\\npronunciation changing over time and with emigration.[30] The same name may\\\\\\\\nappear in different cultures by coincidence or romanization; the surname Lee\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Lee_(English_name)] is used in English culture, but is also a\\\\\\\\nromanization of the Chinese surname Li [/wiki/Li_(surname_%E6%9D%8E)].[46] In\\\\\\\\nthe Russian Empire [/wiki/Russian_Empire], illegitimate children were sometimes\\\\\\\\ngiven artificial surnames [/wiki/Russian_surnames_of_illegitimate_children]\\\\\\\\nrather than the surnames of their adoptive parents.[49][50]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nORDER OF NAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=15]]\\\\\\\\nFurther information: Personal name Name order [/wiki/Personal_name#Name_order]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn many cultures (particularly in European [/wiki/Culture_of_Europe] and\\\\\\\\nEuropean-influenced cultures in the Americas, Oceania, etc., as well as West\\\\\\\\nAsia/North Africa, South Asia, and most Sub-Saharan African cultures), the\\\\\\\\nsurname or family name (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"last name\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") is placed after the personal, forename\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Given_name] (in Europe) or given name (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"first name\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"). In other cultures\\\\\\\\nthe surname is placed first, followed by the given name or names. The latter is\\\\\\\\noften called the Eastern naming order [/wiki/Name_order] because Europeans are\\\\\\\\nmost familiar with the examples from the East Asian cultural sphere\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/East_Asian_cultural_sphere], specifically, Greater China\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Chinese_name], Korea (both North and South) [/wiki/Korean_name], Japan\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Japanese_name], and Vietnam [/wiki/Vietnamese_name]. This is also the\\\\\\\\ncase in Cambodia [/wiki/Cambodia] and among the Hmong [/wiki/Hmong_people] of\\\\\\\\nLaos [/wiki/Laos] and Thailand [/wiki/Thailand]. The Telugu\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Telugu_language] people of south India also place surname before personal\\\\\\\\nname, and historically the Tamil [/wiki/Tamil_language] people did the same.[51]\\\\\\\\nThere are some parts of Europe, in particular Hungary [/wiki/Hungary], where the\\\\\\\\nsurname is placed before the personal name.[52]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSince family names are normally written last in European societies, the terms\\\\\\\\nlast name or surname are commonly used for the family name, while in Japan (with\\\\\\\\nvertical writing) the family name may be referred to as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"upper name\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n(ue-no-namae ()).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWhen people from areas using Eastern naming order write their personal name in\\\\\\\\nthe Latin alphabet [/wiki/Latin_alphabet], it is common to reverse the order of\\\\\\\\nthe given and family names for the convenience of Westerners, so that they know\\\\\\\\nwhich name is the family name for official/formal purposes. Reversing the order\\\\\\\\nof names for the same reason is also customary [/wiki/Norm_(social)] for the\\\\\\\\nBaltic Finnic peoples [/wiki/Baltic_Finns] and the Hungarians\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Hungarian_people], but other Uralic peoples [/wiki/Uralic_languages]\\\\\\\\ntraditionally did not have surnames, perhaps because of the clan [/wiki/Clan]\\\\\\\\nstructure of their societies. The Samis [/wiki/Samis], depending on the\\\\\\\\ncircumstances of their names, either saw no change or did see a transformation\\\\\\\\nof their name. For example: Sire in some cases became Siri,[53] and Htta Jhko\\\\\\\\nsslat became Aslak Jacobsen Htta [/wiki/Aslak_H%C3%A6tta]  as was the norm\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Convention_(norm)]. Recently, integration into the EU and increased\\\\\\\\ncommunications with foreigners prompted many Samis to reverse the order of their\\\\\\\\nfull name to given name followed by surname, to avoid their given name being\\\\\\\\nmistaken for and used as a surname.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIndian surnames may often denote village, profession, and/or caste [/wiki/Caste]\\\\\\\\nand are invariably mentioned along with the personal/first names. However,\\\\\\\\nhereditary last names are not universal. In Telugu\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Telugu_language]-speaking families in south India, surname is placed\\\\\\\\nbefore personal / first name and in most cases it is only shown as an initial\\\\\\\\n(for example 'S.' for Suryapeth).[54]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn English and other languages, although the usual order of names is \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"first\\\\\\\\nmiddle last\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", for the purpose of cataloging in libraries and in citing the names\\\\\\\\nof authors in scholarly papers, the order is changed to \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"last, first middle,\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\nwith the last and first names separated by a comma, and items are alphabetized\\\\\\\\nby the last name.[55][56] In France, Italy, Spain, Belgium [/wiki/Belgium] and\\\\\\\\nLatin America, administrative usage is to put the surname before the first on\\\\\\\\nofficial documents.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nGENDER-SPECIFIC VERSIONS OF SURNAME\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=16]]\\\\\\\\nMain article: Surname inflection [/wiki/Surname_inflection]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Category:Gendered surnames [/wiki/Category:Gendered_surnames]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn most Balto-Slavic languages [/wiki/Balto-Slavic_languages] (such as Latvian,\\\\\\\\nLithuanian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, Russian, Polish, Slovak, Czech, etc.) as well\\\\\\\\nas in Greek [/wiki/Greek_language], Irish, Icelandic [/wiki/Icelandic_language],\\\\\\\\nand Azerbaijani [/wiki/Azerbaijani_language], some surnames change form\\\\\\\\ndepending on the gender of the bearer.[57]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nForms of gendered namesLanguageMale formFemale formReferenceIcelandic\\\\\\\\npatronymics [/wiki/Icelandic_name]Suffix -sonSuffix -dttir[58]Greek surnames\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Greek_name#Family_names]Suffixes -os, -as, -isSuffixes -ou, -a,\\\\\\\\n-i[59]Irish surnames [/wiki/Irish_name#Surnames_and_prefixes]Prefixes Mac, ,\\\\\\\\nUa, MagPrefixes Bean U, Nic, Bean Mhic, N, Mhic, Nig[60]Lithuanian surnames\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Lithuanian_name#Feminine_forms]Suffixes -as, -ys, -is, -usSuffixes -ien,\\\\\\\\n-uvien, -ait, -ut, -it, -yt, -[61]Latvian surnames\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Latvian_name]Suffixes -us, -is, -s, -iSuffixes -a, -e, -iaScottish\\\\\\\\nGaelic surnames [/wiki/Scottish_Gaelic#Names]Prefix Mac-Prefix
