patronymics\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Eastern_Slavic_naming_customs#Grammar]Suffixes -ov, -ev, -in, -iy, -oy,\\\\\\\\n-yy, -ou\\\\\\\\nPatronymics -ovich, -ovych, -yovych, -avichSuffixes -ova, -eva, -ina, -aya\\\\\\\\nPatronymics -ovna, -ivna, -yivna, -ouna[63]Czech\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Czech_name#Female_surnames] and Slovak surnames\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Slovak_name]Suffixes -ov, -, -sk, -ckSuffixes -ov, -, -sk,\\\\\\\\n-ck[64]Polish surnames [/wiki/Polish_names]Suffixes -ski, -cki, -dzkiSuffixes\\\\\\\\n-ska, -cka, -dzka[65]Azerbaijani surnames and patronymics\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Azerbaijani_name]Suffixes -ov, -yev, Patronymic oluSuffixes -ova, -yeva,\\\\\\\\nPatronymic qz\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Slavic languages, substantivized adjective surnames have commonly symmetrical\\\\\\\\nadjective variants for males and females (Podwiski/Podwiska in Polish,\\\\\\\\nNov/Nov in Czech or Slovak, etc.). In the case of nominative and\\\\\\\\nquasi-nominative surnames, the female variant is derived from the male variant\\\\\\\\nby a possessive suffix (Novk/Novkov, Hromada/Hromadov). In Czech and Slovak,\\\\\\\\nthe pure possessive would be Novkova, Hromadova, but the surname evolved to a\\\\\\\\nmore adjectivized form Novkov, Hromadov, to suppress the historical\\\\\\\\npossessivity. Some rare types of surnames are universal and gender-neutral:\\\\\\\\nexamples in Czech are Jan, Martin, Fojt, Kov. These are the archaic form\\\\\\\\nof the possessive, related to the plural name of the family. Such rare surnames\\\\\\\\nare also often used for transgender persons during transition because most\\\\\\\\ncommon surnames are gender-specific.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe informal dialectal female form in Polish and Czech dialects was also -ka\\\\\\\\n(Pawlaczka, Kubeka). With the exception of the -ski/-ska suffix, most feminine\\\\\\\\nforms of surnames are seldom observed in Polish.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nGenerally, inflected languages use names and surnames as living words, not as\\\\\\\\nstatic identifiers. Thus, the pair or the family can be named by a plural form\\\\\\\\nwhich can differ from the singular male and female form. For instance, when the\\\\\\\\nmale form is Novk and the female form Novkov, the family name is Novkovi in\\\\\\\\nCzech and Novkovci in Slovak. When the male form is Hrub and the female form\\\\\\\\nis Hrub, the plural family name is Hrub (or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"rodina Hrubch\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\").[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Greece, if a man called Papadopoulos has a daughter or wife, she will likely\\\\\\\\nbe named Papadopoulou, the genitive form, as if the daughter/wife is \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"of\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" a man\\\\\\\\nnamed Papadopoulos. Likewise, the surnames of daughters and wives of males with\\\\\\\\nsurnames ending in -as will end in -a, and those of daughters and wives of males\\\\\\\\nwith the -is suffix will have the -i suffix.[66]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLatvian, like Lithuanian, uses strictly feminized surnames for women, even in\\\\\\\\nthe case of foreign names. The function of the suffix is purely grammatical.\\\\\\\\nMale surnames ending -e or -a need not be modified for women. Exceptions are:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * The female surnames which correspond to nouns in the sixth declension with\\\\\\\\n   the ending \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"-s\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"  \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Iron\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"iron\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"rock\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n * Surnames of both genders, which are written in the same nominative case form\\\\\\\\n   because they correspond to nouns in the third declension ending in \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"-us\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n   (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Grigus\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Markus\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\")\\\\\\\\n * Surnames based on an adjective have indefinite suffixes typical of\\\\\\\\n   adjectives: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"-s, -a\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Stalts\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Stalta\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") or the specified endings \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"-ais, -\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n   (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"aklais\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"akl\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"diligent\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\").[citation needed\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Iceland, surnames have a gender-specific suffix (-dttir = daughter, -son =\\\\\\\\nson).[67] This was also the case in Denmark, Norway, and Sweden, until they were\\\\\\\\nabolished by law in 1856, 1923, and 1966 respectively.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFinnish used gender-specific suffixes up to 1929 when the Marriage Act forced\\\\\\\\nwomen to use the husband's form of the surname. In 1985, this clause was removed\\\\\\\\nfrom the act.[68]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nUntil at least 1850, women's surnames were suffixed with an -in in Tyrol.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nINDICATION OF FAMILY MEMBERSHIP STATUS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=17]]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Maiden and married names [/wiki/Maiden_and_married_names]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSome Slavic cultures originally distinguished the surnames of married and\\\\\\\\nunmarried women by different suffixes, but this distinction is no longer widely\\\\\\\\nobserved. Some Czech dialects (Southwest-Bohemian) use the form \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Novkojc\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" as\\\\\\\\ninformal for both genders. In the culture of the Sorbs [/wiki/Sorbs] (a.k.a.\\\\\\\\nWends or Lusatians), Sorbian [/wiki/Sorbian_languages] used different female\\\\\\\\nforms for unmarried daughters (Jordanojc, Nowcyc, Kubaec, Markulic), and for\\\\\\\\nwives (Nowakowa, Budarka, Nowcyna, Markulina). In Polish, typical surnames for\\\\\\\\nunmarried women ended -wna, -anka, or -ianka, while the surnames of married\\\\\\\\nwomen used the possessive suffixes -ina or -owa. In Serbia, unmarried women's\\\\\\\\nsurnames ended in -eva, while married women's surnames ended in -ka. In\\\\\\\\nLithuania, if the husband is named Vilkas, his wife will be named Vilkien and\\\\\\\\nhis unmarried daughter will be named Vilkait. Male surnames have suffixes -as,\\\\\\\\n-is, -ius, or -us, unmarried girl surnames ait, -yt, -it or -ut, wife\\\\\\\\nsurnames -ien. These suffixes are also used for foreign names, exclusively for\\\\\\\\ngrammar; Welby, the surname of the present Archbishop of Canterbury\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Justin_Welby] for example, becomes Velbis in Lithuanian, while his wife\\\\\\\\nis Velbien, and his unmarried daughter, Velbait.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMany surnames include prefixes that may or may not be separated by a space or\\\\\\\\npunctuation from the main part of the surname. These are usually not considered\\\\\\\\ntrue compound names, rather single surnames are made up of more than one word.\\\\\\\\nThese prefixes often give hints about the type or origin of the surname\\\\\\\\n(patronymic, toponymic, notable lineage) and include words that mean from [a\\\\\\\\nplace or lineage], and son of/daughter of/child of.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe common Celtic prefixes \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Ua\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (descendant of) and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mac\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mag\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (son\\\\\\\\nof) can be spelled with the prefix as a separate word, yielding \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" Briain\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mac Millan\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" as well as the anglicized \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"O'Brien\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"MacMillan\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Macmillan\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".\\\\\\\\nOther Irish prefixes include N, Nic (daughter of the son of), Mhic, and U\\\\\\\\n(wife of the son of).[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA surname with the prefix \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Fitz\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" can be spelled with the prefix as a separate\\\\\\\\nword, as in \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Fitz William\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", as well as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"FitzWilliam\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Fitzwilliam\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (like, for\\\\\\\\nexample, Robert FitzRoy [/wiki/Robert_FitzRoy]). \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Fitz [/wiki/Fitz]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" comes from\\\\\\\\nFrench (fils) thus making these surnames a form of patronymic.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSURNAME LAW\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=18]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA family name is typically a part of a person's personal name\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Personal_name] and, according to law or custom, is passed or given to\\\\\\\\nchildren from at least one of their parents' family names. The use of family\\\\\\\\nnames is common in most cultures around the world, but each culture has its own\\\\\\\\nrules as to how the names are formed, passed, and used. However, the style of\\\\\\\\nhaving both a family name (surname) and a given name (forename) is far from\\\\\\\\nuniversal (see History below). In many cultures, it is common for people to\\\\\\\\nhave one name or mononym [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/mononym], with some\\\\\\\\ncultures not using family names. Issues of family name arise especially on the\\\\\\\\npassing of a name to a newborn child, the adoption of a common family name on\\\\\\\\nmarriage, the renunciation of a family name, and the changing of a family\\\\\\\\nname.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSurname laws [/wiki/Surname_law] vary around the world. Traditionally in many\\\\\\\\nEuropean countries for the past few hundred years, it was the custom or the law\\\\\\\\nfor a woman, upon marriage, to use her husband's surname and for any children\\\\\\\\nborn to bear the father's surname. If a child's paternity was not known, or if\\\\\\\\nthe putative father [/wiki/Putative_father] denied paternity, the newborn child\\\\\\\\nwould have the surname of the mother. That is still the custom or law in many\\\\\\\\ncountries. The surname for children of married parents is usually inherited from\\\\\\\\nthe father.[69] In recent years, there has been a trend towards equality of\\\\\\\\ntreatment in relation to family names, with women being not automatically\\\\\\\\nrequired, expected or, in some places, even forbidden, to take the husband's\\\\\\\\nsurname on marriage, with the children not automatically being given the\\\\\\\\nfather's surname. In this article, both family name and surname mean the\\\\\\\\npatrilineal [/wiki/Patrilineal] surname, which is handed down from or inherited\\\\\\\\nfrom the father, unless it is explicitly stated otherwise. Thus, the term\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"maternal surname\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" means the patrilineal surname that one's mother inherited\\\\\\\\nfrom either or both of her parents. For a discussion of matrilineal\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Matrilineal] ('mother-line') surnames, passing from mothers to daughters,\\\\\\\\nsee matrilineal surname [/wiki/Matrilineal_surname].[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSURNAME OF WOMEN\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=19]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nKing Henry VIII [/wiki/Henry_VIII] of England (reigned 15091547) ordered that\\\\\\\\nmarital births be recorded under the surname of the father.[5] In England and\\\\\\\\ncultures derived from there, there has long been a tradition for a woman to\\\\\\\\nchange her surname upon marriage from her birth name [/wiki/Name_at_birth] to\\\\\\\\nher husband's family name. (See Maiden and married names\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Maiden_and_married_names].)[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn the Middle Ages, when a man from a lower-status family married an only\\\\\\\\ndaughter from a higher-status family, he would often adopt the wife's family\\\\\\\\nname.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]] In the 18th and 19th\\\\\\\\ncenturies in Britain, bequests were sometimes made contingent upon a man's\\\\\\\\nchanging (or hyphenating) his family name, so that the name of the testator\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Testator] continued.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe United States followed the naming customs and practices of English common\\\\\\\\nlaw and traditions until recent times. The first known instance in the United\\\\\\\\nStates of a woman insisting on the use of her birth name was that of Lucy Stone\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Lucy_Stone] in 1855, and there has been a general increase in the rate of\\\\\\\\nwomen using their birth name. Beginning in the latter half of the 20th century,\\\\\\\\ntraditional naming practices (writes one commentator) were recognized as\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"com[ing] into conflict with current sensitivities about children's and women's\\\\\\\\nrights\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[70] Those changes accelerated a shift away from the interests of the\\\\\\\\nparents to a focus on the best interests of the child. The law in this area\\\\\\\\ncontinues to evolve today mainly in the context of paternity and custody\\\\\\\\nactions.[71]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nNaming conventions in the US have gone through periods of flux, however, and the\\\\\\\\n1990s saw a decline in the percentage of name retention among women.[72] As of\\\\\\\\n2006, more than 80% of American women adopted the husband's family name after\\\\\\\\nmarriage.[73]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIt is rare but not unknown for an English-speaking man to take his wife's family\\\\\\\\nname, whether for personal reasons or as a matter of tradition (such as among\\\\\\\\nmatrilineal [/wiki/Matrilineal] Canadian aboriginal\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/First_Nations_in_Canada] groups, such as the Haida [/wiki/Haida_people]\\\\\\\\nand Gitxsan [/wiki/Gitxsan]). Upon marriage to a woman, men in the United States\\\\\\\\ncan change their surnames to that of their wives, or adopt a combination of both\\\\\\\\nnames with the federal government, through the Social Security Administration\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Social_Security_Administration]. Men may face difficulty doing so on the\\\\\\\\nstate level in some states.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIt is exceedingly rare but does occur in the United States, where a married\\\\\\\\ncouple may choose an entirely new last name by going through a legal change of\\\\\\\\nname. As an alternative, both spouses may adopt a double-barrelled name\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Double-barrelled_name]. For instance, when John Smith and Mary Jones\\\\\\\\nmarry each other, they may become known as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"John Smith-Jones\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mary\\\\\\\\nSmith-Jones\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". A spouse may also opt to use their birth name as a middle name,\\\\\\\\nand e.g. become known as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mary Jones Smith\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]] An additional option, although rarely\\\\\\\\npracticed[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]], is the adoption of\\\\\\\\nthe last name derived from a blend of the prior names, such as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Simones\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", which\\\\\\\\nalso requires a legal name change. Some couples keep their own last names but\\\\\\\\ngive their children hyphenated or combined surnames.[74]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn 1979, the United Nations adopted the Convention on the Elimination of All\\\\\\\\nForms of Discrimination Against Women\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Convention_on_the_Elimination_of_All_Forms_of_Discrimination_Against_Women]\\\\\\\\n(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"CEDAW\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), which declared in effect that women and men, and specifically wife\\\\\\\\nand husband, shall have the same rights to choose a \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"family name\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", as well as a\\\\\\\\nprofession and an occupation.[75]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn some places, civil rights lawsuits or constitutional amendments changed the\\\\\\\\nlaw so that men could also easily change their married names (e.g., in British\\\\\\\\nColumbia and California).[76] Qubec [/wiki/Qu%C3%A9bec] law permits neither\\\\\\\\nspouse to change surnames.[77]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn France, until 1 January 2005, children were required by law to take the\\\\\\\\nsurname of their father. Article 311-21 of the French Civil code\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Civil_code] now permits parents to give their children the family name of\\\\\\\\neither their father, mother, or hyphenation of both  although no more than two\\\\\\\\nnames can be hyphenated. In cases of disagreement, both names are used in\\\\\\\\nalphabetical order.[78] This brought France into line with a 1978 declaration by\\\\\\\\nthe Council of Europe [/wiki/Council_of_Europe] requiring member governments to\\\\\\\\ntake measures to adopt equality of rights in the transmission of family names, a\\\\\\\\nmeasure that was echoed by the United Nations in 1979.[79]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSimilar measures were adopted by West Germany [/wiki/West_Germany] (1976),\\\\\\\\nSweden (1982), Denmark [/wiki/Denmark] (1983), Finland (1985) and Spain (1999).\\\\\\\\nThe European Community has been active in eliminating gender discrimination.\\\\\\\\nSeveral cases concerning discrimination in family names have reached the courts.\\\\\\\\nBurghartz v. Switzerland challenged the lack of an option for husbands to add\\\\\\\\nthe wife's surname to his surname, which they had chosen as the family name when\\\\\\\\nthis option was available for women.[80] Losonci Rose and Rose v. Switzerland\\\\\\\\nchallenged a prohibition on foreign men married to Swiss women keeping their\\\\\\\\nsurname if this option was provided in their national law, an option available\\\\\\\\nto women.[81] nal Tekeli v. Turkey challenged prohibitions on women using their\\\\\\\\nsurname as the family name, an option only available to men.[82] The Court found\\\\\\\\nall these laws to be in violation of the convention.[83]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFrom 1945 to 2021 in the Czech Republic women by law had to use family names\\\\\\\\nwith the ending -ov after the name of their father or husband (so-called\\\\\\\\npechlen). This was seen as discriminatory by a part of the public. Since 1\\\\\\\\nJanuary 2022, Czech women can decide for themselves whether they want to use the\\\\\\\\nfeminine or neutral form of their family name.[84]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCOMPOUND SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=20]]\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/60px-Question_book-new.svg.png]/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg\\\\\\\\nThis section does not cite [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources] any sources\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability]. Please help improve this section\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Special:EditPage/Surname] by adding citations to reliable sources\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners]. Unsourced material may be challenged and\\\\\\\\nremoved [/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence]. (August 2023) (Learn\\\\\\\\nhow and when to remove this message [/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal])\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWhile in many countries surnames are usually one word, in others a surname may\\\\\\\\ncontain two words or more, as described below.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nENGLISH\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=21]]\\\\\\\\nFurther information: Double-barrelled name British tradition\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Double-barrelled_name#British_tradition]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCompound surnames in English and several other European cultures feature two (or\\\\\\\\noccasionally more) words, often joined by a hyphen [/wiki/Hyphen] or hyphens.\\\\\\\\nHowever, it is not unusual for compound surnames to be composed of separate\\\\\\\\nwords not linked by a hyphen, for example Iain Duncan Smith\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Iain_Duncan_Smith], a former leader of the British Conservative Party\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Conservative_Party_(UK)], whose surname is \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Duncan Smith\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[citation\\\\\\\\nneeded [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCHINESE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=22]]\\\\\\\\nMain article: Chinese compound surname [/wiki/Chinese_compound_surname]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSome Chinese surnames [/wiki/Chinese_surname] use more than one character\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Chinese_character] though this is very rare.[85]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMULTIPLE SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=23]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSPANISH-SPEAKING COUNTRIES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=24]]\\\\\\\\nMain articles: Spanish naming customs [/wiki/Spanish_naming_customs] and Naming\\\\\\\\ncustoms of Hispanic America [/wiki/Naming_customs_of_Hispanic_America]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Surnames by country The Philippines\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Surnames_by_country#The_Philippines]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Spain and in most Spanish-speaking countries [/wiki/Hispanophone], the custom\\\\\\\\nis for people to have two surnames, with the first surname coming from the\\\\\\\\nfather and the second from the mother; the opposite order is now legally allowed\\\\\\\\nin Spain but still unusual. In informal situations typically only the first one\\\\\\\\nis used, although both are needed for legal purposes. A child's first surname\\\\\\\\nwill usually be their father's first surname, while the child's second surname\\\\\\\\nwill usually be their mother's first surname. For example, if Jos Garca Torres\\\\\\\\nand Mara Acosta Gmez had a child named Pablo, then his full name would be\\\\\\\\nPablo Garca Acosta. One family member's relationship to another can often be\\\\\\\\nidentified by the various combinations and permutations of surnames.[citation\\\\\\\\nneeded [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nJos Garca TorresMara Acosta GmezPablo Garca Acosta\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn some instances, when an individual's first surname is very common, such as\\\\\\\\nfor example in Jos Luis Rodrguez Zapatero\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Luis_Rodr%C3%ADguez_Zapatero], the second surname tends to gain\\\\\\\\npreeminence over the first one in informal use. Rodrguez Zapatero, therefore is\\\\\\\\nmore often called just Zapatero and almost never Rodrguez only; in other cases,\\\\\\\\nsuch as in writer Mario Vargas Llosa [/wiki/Mario_Vargas_Llosa], a person\\\\\\\\nbecomes usually called by both surnames. This changes from person to person and\\\\\\\\nstems merely from habit.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Spain, feminist activism pushed for a law approved in 1999 that allows an\\\\\\\\nadult to change the order of his/her family names,[86] and parents can also\\\\\\\\nchange the order of their children's family names if they (and the child, if\\\\\\\\nover 12) agree, although this order must be the same for all their\\\\\\\\nchildren.[87][88]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Spain, especially Catalonia [/wiki/Catalonia], the paternal and maternal\\\\\\\\nsurnames are often combined using the conjunction y (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"and\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" in Spanish) or i\\\\\\\\n(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"and\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" in Catalan [/wiki/Catalan_language]), see for example the economist\\\\\\\\nXavier Sala-i-Martin [/wiki/Xavier_Sala-i-Martin] or painter Salvador Dal i\\\\\\\\nDomnech [/wiki/Salvador_Dal%C3%AD].[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Spain, a woman does not generally change her legal surname when she marries.\\\\\\\\nIn some Spanish-speaking countries in Latin America, a woman may, on her\\\\\\\\nmarriage, drop her mother's surname and add her husband's surname to her\\\\\\\\nfather's surname using the preposition de (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"of\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), del (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"of the\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", when the\\\\\\\\nfollowing word is masculine) or de la (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"of the\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", when the following word is\\\\\\\\nfeminine). For example, if \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Clara Reyes Alba\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" were to marry \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Alberto Gmez\\\\\\\\nRodrguez\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", the wife could use \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Clara Reyes de Gmez\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" as her name (or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Clara\\\\\\\\nReyes Gmez\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", or, rarely, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Clara Gmez Reyes\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". She can be addressed as Sra\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Mrs.]. de Gmez corresponding to \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mrs Gmez\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"). Feminist activists have\\\\\\\\ncriticized this custom [when?\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items]] as they\\\\\\\\nconsider it sexist.[89][90] In some countries, this form may be mainly social\\\\\\\\nand not an official name change, i.e. her name would still legally be her birth\\\\\\\\nname. This custom, begun in medieval times, is decaying and only has legal\\\\\\\\nvalidity [citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]] in Dominican\\\\\\\\nRepublic [/wiki/Dominican_Republic], Ecuador [/wiki/Ecuador], Guatemala\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Guatemala], Nicaragua [/wiki/Nicaragua], Honduras [/wiki/Honduras], Peru\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Peru], Panama [/wiki/Panama], and to a certain extent in Mexico (where it\\\\\\\\nis optional but becoming obsolete), but is frowned upon by people in Spain,\\\\\\\\nCuba, and elsewhere. In Peru and the Dominican Republic, women normally conserve\\\\\\\\nall family names after getting married. For example, if Rosa Mara Prez\\\\\\\\nMartnez marries Juan Martn De la Cruz Gmez, she will be called Rosa Mara\\\\\\\\nPrez Martnez de De la Cruz, and if the husband dies, she will be called Rosa\\\\\\\\nMara Prez Martnez Vda. de De la Cruz (Vda. being the abbreviation for viuda,\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"widow\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" in Spanish). The law in Peru changed some years ago, and all married\\\\\\\\nwomen can keep their maiden last name if they wish with no alteration.[citation\\\\\\\\nneeded [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nHistorically, sometimes a father transmitted his combined family names, thus\\\\\\\\ncreating a new one e.g., the paternal surname of the son of Javier (given name)\\\\\\\\nReyes (paternal family name) de la Barrera (maternal surname) may have become\\\\\\\\nthe new paternal surname Reyes de la Barrera. For example, Uruguayan politician\\\\\\\\nGuido Manini Rios [/wiki/Guido_Manini_Rios] has inherited a compound surname\\\\\\\\nconstructed from the patrilineal and matrilineal surnames of a recent ancestor.\\\\\\\\nDe is also the nobiliary particle [/wiki/Nobiliary_particle] used with Spanish\\\\\\\\nsurnames. This can not be chosen by the person, as it is part of the surname,\\\\\\\\nfor example, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Puente\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Del Puente\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" are not the same surname.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSometimes, for single mothers or when the father would or could not recognize\\\\\\\\nthe child, the mother's surname has been used twice: for example, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Ana Reyes\\\\\\\\nReyes\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". In Spain, however, children with just one parent receive both surnames\\\\\\\\nof that parent, although the order may also be changed. In 1973 in Chile, the\\\\\\\\nlaw was changed to avoid stigmatizing illegitimate children with the maternal\\\\\\\\nsurname repeated.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSome Hispanic people, after leaving their country, drop their maternal surname,\\\\\\\\neven if not formally, so as to better fit into the non-Hispanic society they\\\\\\\\nlive or work in. Similarly, foreigners with just one surname may be asked to\\\\\\\\nprovide a second surname on official documents in Spanish-speaking countries.\\\\\\\\nWhen none (such as the mother's maiden name) is provided, the last name may\\\\\\\\nsimply be repeated.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA new trend in the United States for Hispanics is to hyphenate their father's\\\\\\\\nand mother's last names. This is done because American-born English-speakers are\\\\\\\\nnot aware of the Hispanic custom of using two last names and thus mistake the\\\\\\\\nfirst last name of the individual for a middle name. In doing so they would, for\\\\\\\\nexample, mistakenly refer to Esteban lvarez Cobos as Esteban A. Cobos. Such\\\\\\\\nconfusion can be particularly troublesome in official matters. To avoid such\\\\\\\\nmistakes, Esteban lvarez Cobos, would become Esteban lvarez-Cobos, to clarify\\\\\\\\nthat both are last names.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn some churches, such as the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, where\\\\\\\\nthe family structure is emphasized, as well as a legal marriage, the wife is\\\\\\\\nreferred to as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"hermana\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" [sister] plus the surname of her husband. And most\\\\\\\\nrecords of the church follow that structure as well.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nINFORMAL TRADITIONAL NAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=25]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn many places, such as villages in Catalonia, Galicia [/wiki/Galicia_(Spain)],\\\\\\\\nand Asturias [/wiki/Asturias] and in Cuba, people are often informally known by\\\\\\\\nthe name of their dwelling or collective family nickname rather than by their\\\\\\\\nsurnames. For example, Remei Pujol i Serra who lives at Ca l'Elvira would be\\\\\\\\nreferred to as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Remei de Ca l'Elvira\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"; and Adela Barreira Lpez who is part of\\\\\\\\nthe \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Provisores\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" family would be known as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Adela dos Provisores\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".[citation\\\\\\\\nneeded [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAlso in many places, such as Cantabria [/wiki/Cantabria], the family's nickname\\\\\\\\nis used instead of the surname: if one family is known as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"ecos\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" because of an\\\\\\\\nancestor who was known as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"ecu\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", they would be \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Jos el de ecu\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Ana la de\\\\\\\\necu\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (collective: the eco's). Some common nicknames are \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Rubiu\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (blond or red\\\\\\\\nhair), \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Roju\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (reddish, referring to their red hair), \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Chiqui\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (small), \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Jinchu\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n(big), and a bunch of names about certain characteristics, family relationship\\\\\\\\nor geographical origin (pasiegu, masoniegu, sobanu, llebaniegu, tresmeranu,\\\\\\\\npejinu, naveru, merachu, tresneru, troule, mallavia, marotias, llamoso, lipa,\\\\\\\\necu, tarugu, trapajeru, lichn, andarvel).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCOMPOUND SURNAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=26]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nBeyond the seemingly \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"compound\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" surname system in the Spanish-speaking world,\\\\\\\\nthere are also true compound surnames. These true compound surnames are passed\\\\\\\\non and inherited as compounds. For instance, former chairman of the Supreme\\\\\\\\nMilitary Junta [/wiki/Military_junta] of Ecuador [/wiki/Ecuador], General Luis\\\\\\\\nTelmo Paz y Mio [/wiki/Luis_Telmo_Paz_y_Mi%C3%B1o] Estrella, has Luis\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Luis] as his first given name, Telmo as his middle name, the true\\\\\\\\ncompound surname Paz y Mio as his first (i.e. paternal) surname, and Estrella\\\\\\\\nas his second (i.e. maternal) surname. Luis Telmo Paz y Mio Estrella is also\\\\\\\\nknown more casually as Luis Paz y Mio, Telmo Paz y Mio, or Luis Telmo Paz y\\\\\\\\nMio. He would never be regarded as Luis Estrella, Telmo Estrella, or Luis Telmo\\\\\\\\nEstrella, nor as Luis Paz, Telmo Paz, or Luis Telmo Paz. This is because \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Paz\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\nalone is not his surname (although other people use the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Paz\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" surname on its\\\\\\\\nown).[69] In this case, Paz y Mio [/wiki/Pazmi%C3%B1o] is in fact the paternal\\\\\\\\nsurname, being a true compound surname. His children, therefore, would inherit\\\\\\\\nthe compound surname \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Paz y Mio\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" as their paternal surname, while Estrella\\\\\\\\nwould be lost, since the mother's paternal surname becomes the children's second\\\\\\\\nsurname (as their own maternal surname). \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Paz\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" alone would not be passed on, nor\\\\\\\\nwould \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mio\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" alone.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nTo avoid ambiguity, one might often informally see these true compound surnames\\\\\\\\nhyphenated, for instance, as Paz-y-Mio. This is true especially in the\\\\\\\\nEnglish-speaking world [/wiki/English-speaking_world], but also sometimes even\\\\\\\\nin the Hispanic world, since many Hispanics are unfamiliar with this and other\\\\\\\\ncompound surnames, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Paz y Mio\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" might be inadvertently mistaken as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Paz\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" for the\\\\\\\\npaternal surname and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mio\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" for the maternal surname. Although Mio did start\\\\\\\\noff as the maternal surname in this compound surname, it was many generations\\\\\\\\nago, around five centuries, that it became compounded, and henceforth inherited\\\\\\\\nand passed on as a compound.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOther surnames which started off as compounds of two or more surnames, but which\\\\\\\\nmerged into one single word, also exist. An example would be the surname Pazmio\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Pazmi%C3%B1o], whose members are related to the Paz y Mio, as both\\\\\\\\ndescend from the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Paz Mio\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" family[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]] of five centuries ago.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nlava [/wiki/%C3%81lava], Spain is known for its incidence of true compound\\\\\\\\nsurnames, characterized for having the first portion of the surname as a\\\\\\\\npatronymic, normally a Spanish patronymic or more unusually a Basque\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Basque_language] patronymic, followed by the preposition\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Preposition] \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"de\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", with the second part of the surname being a placename\\\\\\\\nfrom lava.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPORTUGUESE-SPEAKING COUNTRIES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=27]]\\\\\\\\nMain article: Portuguese name [/wiki/Portuguese_name]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn Portuguese naming customs, the main surname (the one used in alpha sorting,\\\\\\\\nindexing, abbreviations, and greetings), appears last.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEach person usually has two family names: though the law specifies no order, the\\\\\\\\nfirst one is usually the maternal family name and the last one is commonly the\\\\\\\\npaternal family name. In Portugal, a person's full name has a minimum legal\\\\\\\\nlength of two names (one given name and one family name from either parent) and\\\\\\\\na maximum of six names (two first names and four surnames  he or she may have\\\\\\\\nup to four surnames in any order desired picked up from the total of his/her\\\\\\\\nparents and grandparents' surnames). The use of any surname outside this lot, or\\\\\\\\nof more than six names, is legally possible, but it requires dealing with\\\\\\\\nbureaucracy. Parents or the person him/herself must explain the claims they have\\\\\\\\nto bear that surname (a family nickname, a rare surname lost in past\\\\\\\\ngenerations, or any other reason one may find suitable). In Brazil, there is no\\\\\\\\nlimit of surnames used.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn the Portuguese tradition, the mother's surname usually comes first, followed\\\\\\\\nby the father's surname. A woman may adopt her husband's surname(s), but\\\\\\\\nnevertheless, she usually keeps her birth name or at least the last one. Since\\\\\\\\n1977 in Portugal and 2012 in Brazil, a husband can also adopt his wife's\\\\\\\\nsurname. When this happens, usually both spouses change their name after\\\\\\\\nmarriage.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe custom of a woman changing her name upon marriage is recent. It spread in\\\\\\\\nthe late 19th century in the upper classes, under French influence, and in the\\\\\\\\n20th century, particularly during the 1930s and 1940, it became socially almost\\\\\\\\nobligatory. Nowadays, fewer women adopt, even officially, their husbands' names,\\\\\\\\nand among those who do so officially, it is quite common not to use it either in\\\\\\\\ntheir professional or informal life.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe children usually bear only the last surnames of the parents (i.e., the\\\\\\\\npaternal surname of each of their parents). For example, Carlos da Silva\\\\\\\\nGonalves and Ana Lusa de Albuquerque Pereira (Gonalves) (in case she adopted\\\\\\\\nher husband's name after marriage) would have a child named Lucas Pereira\\\\\\\\nGonalves. However, the child may have any other combination of the parents'\\\\\\\\nsurnames, according to euphony [/wiki/Euphony], social significance, or other\\\\\\\\nreasons. For example, is not uncommon for the firstborn male to be given the\\\\\\\\nfather's full name followed by \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Jnior\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Filho\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (son), and the next\\\\\\\\ngeneration's firstborn male to be given the grandfather's name followed by\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Neto\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (grandson). Hence Carlos da Silva Gonalves might choose to name his\\\\\\\\nfirst born son Carlos da Silva Gonalves Jnior, who in turn might name his\\\\\\\\nfirst born son Carlos da Silva Gonalves Neto, in which case none of the\\\\\\\\nmother's family names are passed on.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCarlos da Silva GonalvesAna Lusa de Albuquerque PereiraLucas Pereira Gonalves\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn ancient times a patronymic was commonly used  surnames like Gonalves (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"son\\\\\\\\nof Gonalo\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), Fernandes (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"son of Fernando\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), Nunes (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"son of Nuno\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), Soares (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"son\\\\\\\\nof Soeiro\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), Sanches (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"son of Sancho\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), Henriques (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"son of Henrique\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"), Rodrigues\\\\\\\\n(\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"son of Rodrigo\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") which along with many others are still in regular use as very\\\\\\\\nprevalent family names.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn medieval times, Portuguese nobility started to use one of their estates'\\\\\\\\nnames or the name of the town or village they ruled as their surname, just after\\\\\\\\ntheir patronymic. Soeiro Mendes da Maia\\\\\\\\n[/w/index.php?title=Soeiro_Mendes_da_Maia&action=edit&redlink=1] bore a name\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Soeiro\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", a patronymic \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mendes\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"son of Hermenegildo  shortened to Mendo\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") and\\\\\\\\nthe name of the town he ruled \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Maia [/wiki/Maia,_Porto,_Portugal]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". He was often\\\\\\\\nreferred to in 12th-century documents as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Soeiro Mendes, senhor da Maia\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", Soeiro\\\\\\\\nMendes, lord of Maia. Noblewomen also bore patronymics and surnames in the same\\\\\\\\nmanner and never bore their husband's surnames. First-born males bore their\\\\\\\\nfather's surname, other children bore either both or only one of them at their\\\\\\\\nwill.[citation needed [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOnly during the Early Modern Age, lower-class males started to use at least one\\\\\\\\nsurname; married lower-class women usually took up their spouse's surname, since\\\\\\\\nthey rarely ever used one beforehand. After the 1755 Lisbon earthquake\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/1755_Lisbon_earthquake], Portuguese authorities realized the benefits of\\\\\\\\nenforcing the use and registry of surnames. Henceforth, they became mandatory,\\\\\\\\nalthough the rules for their use were very liberal.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nUntil the end of the 19th century, it was common for women, especially those\\\\\\\\nfrom a very poor background, not to have a surname and so to be known only by\\\\\\\\ntheir first names. A woman would then adopt her husband's full surname after\\\\\\\\nmarriage. With the advent of republicanism in Brazil and Portugal, along with\\\\\\\\nthe institution of civil registries, all children now have surnames.During the\\\\\\\\nmid-20th century, under French influence and among upper classes, women started\\\\\\\\nto take up their husbands' surname(s). From the 1960s onwards, this usage spread\\\\\\\\nto the common people, again under French influence, this time, however, due to\\\\\\\\nthe forceful legal adoption of their husbands' surname which was imposed onto\\\\\\\\nPortuguese immigrant women in France.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFrom the 1974 Carnation Revolution [/wiki/Carnation_Revolution] onwards the\\\\\\\\nadoption of their husbands' surname(s) receded again, and today both the\\\\\\\\nadoption and non-adoption occur, with non-adoption being chosen in the majority\\\\\\\\nof cases in recent years (60%).[91] Also, it is legally possible for the husband\\\\\\\\nto adopt his wife's surname(s), but this practice is rare.[citation needed\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0b/Map_of_Most_Commons_Surnames_in_the_United_States_by_State.svg/250px-Map_of_Most_Commons_Surnames_in_the_United_States_by_State.svg.png]/wiki/File:Map_of_Most_Commons_Surnames_in_the_United_States_by_State.svgMap\\\\\\\\nof Most Common Surnames in the United States by State\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPREVALENCE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=28]]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Lists of most common surnames [/wiki/Lists_of_most_common_surnames]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn the United States, 1,712 surnames cover 50% of the population, and about 1%\\\\\\\\nof the population has the surname Smith [/wiki/Smith_(surname)], the most common\\\\\\\\nAmerican name.[92]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAccording to some estimates, 85% of China's population shares just 100 surnames.\\\\\\\\nThe names Wang (), Zhang (), and Li () are the most frequent.[93]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSEE ALSO\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[edit [/w/index.php?title=Surname&action=edit&section=29]]\\\\\\\\n * Dit name [/wiki/Dit_name]\\\\\\\\n * semi-protected\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/1b/Semi-protection-shackle.svg/20px-Semi-protection-shackle.svg.png]/wiki/Wikipedia:Protection_policy#semi\\\\\\\\nFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIntroduction to English language Wikipedia\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * WP:ABT [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:ABT&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * WP:ABOUT\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:ABOUT&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * WP:WIKIPEDIA\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:WIKIPEDIA&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThis is a general introduction [/wiki/Wikipedia:INFOPAGES] for visitors to\\\\\\\\nWikipedia. For aspiring contributors, also see this guide\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Contributing_to_Wikipedia] and tutorial\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Introduction]. For other uses, see Wikipedia:Wikipedia\\\\\\\\n(disambiguation) [/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_(disambiguation)].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Imagine a world in which every single person on the planet is given free access\\\\\\\\nto the sum of all human knowledge. That's what we're doing.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" Jimmy Wales\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Jimmy_Wales]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWikipedia [/wiki/Wikipedia] is a free online encyclopedia\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Free_encyclopedia] that anyone can edit, and millions already\\\\\\\\nhave [/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedians#Number_of_editors].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWikipedia's purpose [/wiki/Wikipedia:Purpose] is to benefit readers by\\\\\\\\npresenting information on all branches of knowledge [/wiki/Knowledge]. Hosted by\\\\\\\\nthe Wikimedia Foundation [/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikimedia_Foundation], Wikipedia\\\\\\\\nconsists of freely editable [/wiki/Help:Editing] content, with articles that\\\\\\\\nusually contain numerous links guiding readers to more information.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWritten collaboratively [/wiki/Collaborative_writing] by volunteers known as\\\\\\\\nWikipedians [/wiki/Wikipedia_community], Wikipedia articles can be edited by\\\\\\\\nanyone with Internet access [/wiki/Internet_access], except in limited cases\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Protection_policy] in which editing [/wiki/Editing] is\\\\\\\\nrestricted to prevent disruption [/wiki/Wikipedia:Disruption] or vandalism\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:VAND]. Since its creation on January 15, 2001\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia_Day], it has grown into the world's largest\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Size_of_Wikipedia] reference website [/wiki/Website],\\\\\\\\nattracting over a billion visitors each month\\\\\\\\n[https://stats.wikimedia.org/#/all-wikipedia-projects/reading/unique-devices].\\\\\\\\nWikipedia currently has more than sixty-four million articles\\\\\\\\n[https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/List_of_Wikipedias#All_Wikipedias_ordered_by_number_of_articles]\\\\\\\\nin more than 300 languages [/wiki/Special:SiteMatrix], including 6,980,650\\\\\\\\narticles in English [/wiki/English_language], with 120,562 active contributors\\\\\\\\nin the past month.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWikipedia's fundamental principles are summarized in its five pillars\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Five_pillars]. While the Wikipedia community\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia_community] has developed many policies and guidelines\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Policies_and_guidelines], new editors do not need to be\\\\\\\\nfamiliar with them before they start contributing.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAnyone [/wiki/Wikipedia:Who_writes_Wikipedia%3F] can edit [/wiki/Help:Editing]\\\\\\\\nWikipedia's text, data, references, and images. The quality of content is more\\\\\\\\nimportant than the expertise of who contributes it. Wikipedia's content must\\\\\\\\nconform with its policies [/wiki/Wikipedia:Editing_policy], including being\\\\\\\\nverifiable [/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiable] by published reliable sources\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Reliable_sources]. Contributions based on personal opinions\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view], beliefs, or personal experiences,\\\\\\\\nunreviewed research [/wiki/Wikipedia:Original_research], libellous material, and\\\\\\\\ncopyright violations [/wiki/Wikipedia:Copyright_violations] are not allowed, and\\\\\\\\nwill not remain. Wikipedia's software makes it easy to reverse errors, and\\\\\\\\nexperienced editors [/wiki/Wikipedia_editor] watch [/wiki/Wikipedia:Watchlist]\\\\\\\\nand patrol [/wiki/Wikipedia:Recent_changes_patrol] bad edits.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWikipedia differs from printed references in important ways\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTPAPER]. Anyone can instantly improve it, add quality\\\\\\\\ninformation, remove misinformation, and fix errors and vandalism\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Vandalism]. Since Wikipedia is continually updated,\\\\\\\\nencyclopedic articles on major news events appear within minutes.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFor over 24 years, editors have volunteered their time and talents to create\\\\\\\\nhistory's most comprehensive encyclopedia while providing references and other\\\\\\\\nresources to researchers worldwide (see Researching with Wikipedia\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Researching_with_Wikipedia]). In summary, Wikipedia has tested\\\\\\\\nthe wisdom of the crowd [/wiki/Wisdom_of_the_crowd] since 2001 and has found\\\\\\\\nthat it succeeds.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n> To start editing simply click the Edit or Editsourcebutton, or the pencil\\\\\\\\n> icon[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/Pencil_edit_icon.svg/22px-Pencil_edit_icon.svg.png]/wiki/File:Pencil_edit_icon.svg,\\\\\\\\n> at the top of any non-protected [/wiki/Wikipedia:Protection_policy] Wikipedia\\\\\\\\n> page or section.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * v [/wiki/Template:Basic_information]\\\\\\\\n * t [/wiki/Template_talk:Basic_information]\\\\\\\\n * e [/wiki/Special:EditPage/Template:Basic_information]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nBasic information on Wikipedia [/wiki/Category:Wikipedia_basic_information] -\\\\\\\\n(Search [/wiki/Help:Searching#Custom_search_boxes])\\\\\\\\n * Help [/wiki/Help:Contents]\\\\\\\\n   * directory [/wiki/Help:Directory]\\\\\\\\n   * menu [/wiki/Help:Menu]\\\\\\\\n * Teahouse [/wiki/Wikipedia:Teahouse] (interactive help for new editors)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAbout Wikipedia\\\\\\\\n * Readers' index to Wikipedia [/wiki/Wikipedia:Reader%27s_index_to_Wikipedia]\\\\\\\\n * Statistics [/wiki/Wikipedia:Statistics]\\\\\\\\n * Administration [/wiki/Wikipedia:Administration]\\\\\\\\n * FAQs [/wiki/Wikipedia:FAQ/Index]\\\\\\\\n   * Purpose [/wiki/Wikipedia:Purpose]\\\\\\\\n   * Who writes Wikipedia? [/wiki/Wikipedia:Village_pump_(miscellaneous)]\\\\\\\\nPost messages that do not fit into any other category\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCOMMUNITY BULLETIN BOARD\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThis section is transcluded [/wiki/Help:Transclusion] from Wikipedia:Community\\\\\\\\nbulletin board [/wiki/Wikipedia:Community_bulletin_board]. (edit\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:Community_bulletin_board&action=edit]\\\\\\\\n| history\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:Community_bulletin_board&action=history])\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Ambox_notice.png/20px-Ambox_notice.png]/wiki/File:Ambox_notice.png\\\\\\\\nHow to add to the community bulletin board\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/1d/Information_icon4.svg/40px-Information_icon4.svg.png]The\\\\\\\\ncommunity bulletin board has 2 sections that can be used by Wikipedians for\\\\\\\\nannouncements: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Events and projects\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"WikiProject notices\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". In general, keep\\\\\\\\nit concise (under 2 lines), refrain from fancy formatting, and new entries\\\\\\\\nshould be placed at the top of their section.\\\\\\\\n * Before editing, make sure you are on Wikipedia:Community bulletin board\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:Community_bulletin_board], not Wikipedia:Community portal,\\\\\\\\n   where the board is transcluded.\\\\\\\\n * Events and projects: In this section, only organized events, projects, and/or\\\\\\\\n   competitions should be listed. These are organized by how often they occur:\\\\\\\\n   * The Yearly section is for uncommon events, like events that only occur\\\\\\\\n     every year, once, or irregularly. The Monthly section is for events that\\\\\\\\n     occur each month, or are always ongoing.\\\\\\\\n * WikiProject notices: In this section, any announcement, request for help or\\\\\\\\n   other notice from a WikiProject should be listed here.\\\\\\\\n   * Entries should be signed, and ordered from newest to oldest.\\\\\\\\n   * Entries are to be removed after a period of 6 months.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWelcome to the community bulletin board, which is a page used for announcements\\\\\\\\nfrom WikiProjects [/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikiproject] and other groups. Included here\\\\\\\\nare coordinated efforts, events, projects, and other general announcements.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Dashboard [/wiki/Wikipedia:Dashboard]\\\\\\\\n * News [/wiki/Wikipedia:News]\\\\\\\\n * Task Center [/wiki/Wikipedia:Task_Center]\\\\\\\\n * Goings-on [/wiki/Wikipedia:Goings-on]\\\\\\\\n * Meetups [/wiki/Wikipedia:Meetups]\\\\\\\\n * In the media [/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_in_the_media]\\\\\\\\n * Mailing lists [/wiki/Wikipedia:Mailing_lists]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEvents and projects [add]\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Special:EditPage/Wikipedia:Community_bulletin_board]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nYearly or infrequent events\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * The Core Contest [/wiki/Wikipedia:The_Core_Contest]. April 15 - May 31, an\\\\\\\\n   contest to improve broad and important articles, together with others or\\\\\\\\n   alone. Sign-ups are open [/wiki/Wikipedia:The_Core_Contest/Entries] until the\\\\\\\\n   end of the competition.\\\\\\\\n * Wikidata and Sister Projects\\\\\\\\n   [https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Event:Wikidata_and_Sister_Projects]. May 29 -\\\\\\\\n   June 1, an online event exploring the different ways Wikidata is connected\\\\\\\\n   and used in the other Wikimedia projects, including Wikipedia. We are\\\\\\\\n   currently accepting session proposals for the event program, you can submit\\\\\\\\n   them here\\\\\\\\n   [https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Event_talk:Wikidata_and_Sister_Projects], or\\\\\\\\n   ask any questions you may have!\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMonthly or continuous events\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Monthly contest, WikiProject Military history\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Military_history/Contest]. The contest\\\\\\\\n   department of the Military history WikiProject aims to motivate increased\\\\\\\\n   quality in military history articles by offering a form of friendly\\\\\\\\n   competition for project members making improvements to them. The primary\\\\\\\\n   contest available is a simple rolling competition that awards points for\\\\\\\\n   improving articles. The contest runs from the first to last day of each\\\\\\\\n   month.\\\\\\\\n * Guild of Copy Editors' editing blitz. The April 2025 editing blitz\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Guild_of_Copy_Editors/Blitzes/April_2025] is a\\\\\\\\n   one-week-long effort by the Guild of Copy Editors [/wiki/Wikipedia:GOCE] to\\\\\\\\n   reduce its backlog. The themes are: articles on the GOCE Requests page\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:GOCE/REQ] from January to April 2025, and articles on the\\\\\\\\n   backlog from September 2023\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Category:Wikipedia_articles_needing_copy_edit_from_September_2023] and\\\\\\\\n   October 2023\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Category:Wikipedia_articles_needing_copy_edit_from_October_2023]. It\\\\\\\\n   began on 13 April, 00:00 (UTC), and will end on 19 April, 23:59 (UTC).\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:WikiProject Women in Red [/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Women_in_Red]\\\\\\\\n   2024 Events:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nRecently completed: Alphabet run: E & F\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Women_in_Red/Meetup/332] The Transhumanist [/wiki/User:The_Transhumanist]\\\\\\\\n     11:59, 29 March 2025 (UTC)\\\\\\\\n     [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Community_portal#c-The_Transhumanist-20250329115900-Sheriff_U3-20250405125100]\\\\\\\\n * WP Unreferenced articles [/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Unreferenced_articles]\\\\\\\\n   is trying to clear the decades-long backlog of unreferenced articles\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Category:Articles_lacking_sources]. The backlog recently reached under\\\\\\\\n   67,000 -- down from 90,000 half a year ago. Come contribute! Mrfoogles\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/User:Mrfoogles] (talk [/wiki/User_talk:Mrfoogles]) 21:44, 12 March\\\\\\\\n   2025 (UTC)\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Community_portal#c-Mrfoogles-20250312214400-Sheriff_U3-20250405125100]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nTechnical news [/wiki/Wikipedia:Tech_news]\\\\\\\\nThis section is transcluded [/wiki/Help:Transclusion] from Wikipedia:Tech news\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Tech_news]. (edit\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:Tech_news&action=edit] |\\\\\\\\nhistory\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:Tech_news&action=history])\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLatest tech news [https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Tech/News]\\\\\\\\nfrom the Wikimedia technical community. Please tell other users about these\\\\\\\\nchanges. Not all changes will affect you. Translations\\\\\\\\n[https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Tech/News/2025/15] are\\\\\\\\navailable.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nUpdates for editors\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * From now on, interface admins\\\\\\\\n   [https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Interface_administrators]\\\\\\\\n   and centralnotice admins\\\\\\\\n   [https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Central_notice_administrators]\\\\\\\\n   are technically required to enable two-factor authentication\\\\\\\\n   [https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Help:Two-factor_authentication]\\\\\\\\n   before they can use their privileges. In the future this might be expanded to\\\\\\\\n   more groups with advanced user-rights. [1]\\\\\\\\n   [https://phabricator.wikimedia.org/T150898]\\\\\\\\n * Recurrent item\\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Octicons-sync.svg/20px-Octicons-sync.svg.png]\\\\\\\\n   View all 20 community-submitted tasks that were resolved last week\\\\\\\\n   [https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Tech/News/Recently_resolved_community_tasks].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nUpdates for technical contributors\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * The Design System Team is preparing to release the next major version of\\\\\\\\n   Codex (v2.0.0) on April 29. Editors and developers who use CSS from Codex\\\\\\\\n   should see the 2.0 overview documentation\\\\\\\\n   [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Codex/Release_Timeline/2.0], which includes\\\\\\\\n   guidance related to a few of the breaking changes such as font-size,\\\\\\\\n   line-height, and size-icon.\\\\\\\\n * The results of the Developer Satisfaction Survey (2025)\\\\\\\\n   [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Developer_Satisfaction_Survey/2025] are now\\\\\\\\n   available. Thank you to all participants. These results help the Foundation\\\\\\\\n   decide what to work on next and to review what they recently worked on.\\\\\\\\n * Recurrent item\\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Octicons-sync.svg/20px-Octicons-sync.svg.png]\\\\\\\\n   Detailed code updates later this week: MediaWiki\\\\\\\\n   [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/MediaWiki_1.44/wmf.24]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMeetings and events\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * The 2025 Wikimedia Hackathon\\\\\\\\n   [https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Special:MyLanguage/Wikimedia_Hackathon_2025]\\\\\\\\n   will take place in Istanbul, Turkey, between 24 May. Registration for\\\\\\\\n   attending the in-person event will close on 13 April. Before registering,\\\\\\\\n   please note the potential need for a visa\\\\\\\\n   [https://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkish-representations.en.mfa] or e-visa\\\\\\\\n   [https://www.mfa.gov.tr/visa-information-for-foreigners.en.mfa] to enter the\\\\\\\\n   country.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nTech news [/wiki/Wikipedia:Tip_of_the_day]\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/64/Simple_light_bulb_graphic.png/120px-Simple_light_bulb_graphic.png]\\\\\\\\nMotto of the day...\\\\\\\\nDon't Panic!\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe Motto of the Day (MOTD) [/wiki/Wikipedia:MOTD] is a way of displaying an\\\\\\\\ninspirational or intellectually invigorating daily quote for fellow Wikipedians.\\\\\\\\nIt is designed to be easily added to your user page(s).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThere are several formats to choose from. The random motto version{{Random\\\\\\\\nmotto [/wiki/Template:Random_motto]}}is displayed above. It shows a different\\\\\\\\nmotto each time you refresh the page. Add the template (including the four curly\\\\\\\\nbraces [/wiki/Bracket]) to your User page [/wiki/Special:MyPage].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPrior tip [/wiki/Wikipedia:Tip_of_the_day/April_12]Tips library\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Tips]Next tip [/wiki/Wikipedia:Tip_of_the_day/April_14]\\\\\\\\nRead more:\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:Motto of the day [/wiki/Wikipedia:Motto_of_the_day]\\\\\\\\n * your user page, use {{totd\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Template:Totd]}}\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWikipedia:Community portal at Wikipedia's sister
