Internal links [/wiki/Internal_link] bind the project together into\\\\\\\\nan interconnected whole [/wiki/Web_navigation]. Interwikimedia links\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Interwikimedia_links] bind the project to sister projects such as\\\\\\\\nWikisource [/wiki/Wikisource], Wiktionary [/wiki/Wiktionary] and Wikipedia\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia] in other languages, and external links bind Wikipedia to the\\\\\\\\nWorld Wide Web [/wiki/World_Wide_Web].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAppropriate links provide instant pathways to locations within and outside the\\\\\\\\nproject that can increase readers' understanding of the topic at hand. Whenever\\\\\\\\nwriting or editing an article, consider not only what to put in the article, but\\\\\\\\nalso what links to include to help the reader find related information, and also\\\\\\\\nwhich other pages should have links to the article. Avoid both underlinking and\\\\\\\\noverlinking, as described below.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThis page provides guidelines as to when links should and should not be used,\\\\\\\\nand how to format links. For information about the syntax used to create links,\\\\\\\\nsee Help:Link [/wiki/Help:Link]. For links on disambiguation\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Disambiguation] pages, see Wikipedia:Manual of\\\\\\\\nStyle/Disambiguation pages\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Disambiguation_pages].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPRINCIPLES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"WP:BUILD\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" redirects here. For the behavioral guideline, see Wikipedia:Here to\\\\\\\\nbuild an encyclopedia [/wiki/Wikipedia:Here_to_build_an_encyclopedia].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:BTW [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:BTW&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:BUILD [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:BUILD&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWikipedia is based on hypertext [/wiki/Hypertext], and aims to \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"build the web\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\nto enable readers to access relevant information on other Wikipedia pages\\\\\\\\neasily. The page from which the hyperlink is activated is called the anchor; the\\\\\\\\npage the link points to is called the target.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn adding or removing links, consider an article's place in the knowledge tree\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Tree_structure]. Internal links can add to the cohesion and utility of\\\\\\\\nWikipedia, allowing readers to deepen their understanding of a topic by\\\\\\\\nconveniently accessing other articles. Ask yourself, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"How likely is it that the\\\\\\\\nreader will also want to read that other article?\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" Consider including links\\\\\\\\nwhere readers might want to use them; for example, in article leads\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section], at the openings of new sections,\\\\\\\\nin the cells of tables [/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Tables], and in file\\\\\\\\ncaptions [/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Captions]. But as a rule of thumb,\\\\\\\\nlink only the first occurrence of a term in the text of the article.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nGENERAL POINTS ON LINKING STYLE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:LINKSTYLE\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:LINKSTYLE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:INTERNAL\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:INTERNAL&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * As explained in more detail at Help:Link Wikilinks\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Help:Link#Wikilinks], linking can be direct ([[Riverside,\\\\\\\\n   California]], which results in Riverside, California\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Riverside,_California]), or piped ([[Riverside,\\\\\\\\n   California|Riverside]], which results in Riverside\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Riverside,_California] in the text, but still links to the article\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Riverside, California [/wiki/Riverside,_California]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"although the pipe trick\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Help:Pipe_trick] is an easier way to create this particular link).\\\\\\\\n * Shortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n    * MOS:HEADINGLINK\\\\\\\\n      [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:HEADINGLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\n   Section headings should not themselves contain links; instead, a {{main\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Template:Main]}} or {{see also [/wiki/Template:See_also]}} template\\\\\\\\n   should be placed immediately after the heading.\\\\\\\\n * Links should not be placed [/wiki/MOS:BOLDLINKAVOID] in the boldface\\\\\\\\n   reiteration of the title\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section#Format_of_the_first_sentence]\\\\\\\\n   in the opening sentence of a lead.[a]\\\\\\\\n * Shortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n    * MOS:NOLINKQUOTE\\\\\\\\n      [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:NOLINKQUOTE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\n   Be conservative when linking within quotations [/wiki/Wikipedia:Quotation];\\\\\\\\n   link only to targets that correspond to the meaning clearly intended by the\\\\\\\\n   quote's author. Where possible, link from text outside of the quotation\\\\\\\\n   instead  either before it or soon after.[b]\\\\\\\\n * Shortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n    * MOS:SOB [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:SOB&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n    * MOS:SEAOFBLUE\\\\\\\\n      [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:SEAOFBLUE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n    * MOS:WINGSUIT\\\\\\\\n      [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:WINGSUIT&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\n   When possible, do not place links next to each other, to avoid appearing like\\\\\\\\n   a single link, as in wingsuit [/wiki/Wingsuit]combat [/wiki/Combat]\\\\\\\\n   ([[wingsuit]][[combat]]) or chess [/wiki/Chess] tournament\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Tournament] ([[chess]][[tournament]]). Instead, consider using a\\\\\\\\n   single, more specific link such as chess tournament [/wiki/Chess_tournament]\\\\\\\\n   ([[chess tournament]]), or if not possible, consider omitting one of the\\\\\\\\n   links (chess [/wiki/Chess]tournament) or rephrasing the sentence (tournament\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Tournament] of chess [/wiki/Chess]).\\\\\\\\n * Shortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n    * MOS:GEOLINK\\\\\\\\n      [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:GEOLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\n   For a geographical location expressed as a consecutive comma-separated\\\\\\\\n   sequence of two or more territorial units, link only the first unit.\\\\\\\\n   * For example, avoid\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/X_mark.svg/20px-X_mark.svg.png]NSydney\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Sydney], Australia [/wiki/Australia] ([[Sydney]], [[Australia]])or\\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/X_mark.svg/20px-X_mark.svg.png]NQuothquan\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Quothquan], South Lanarkshire [/wiki/South_Lanarkshire], Scotland\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Scotland] ([[Quothquan]], [[South Lanarkshire]], [[Scotland]])or\\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/X_mark.svg/20px-X_mark.svg.png]NBuffalo\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Buffalo,_New_York], New York [/wiki/New_York_(state)], United States\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/United_States] ([[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[New York (state)|New\\\\\\\\n   York]],[[United States]])\\\\\\\\n   * Instead, use\\\\\\\\n   check\\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/20px-Yes_check.svg.png]YSydney\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Sydney], Australia ([[Sydney]], Australia)orcheck\\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/20px-Yes_check.svg.png]YQuothquan\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Quothquan], South Lanarkshire, Scotland ([[Quothquan]], South\\\\\\\\n   Lanarkshire, Scotland)orcheck\\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/20px-Yes_check.svg.png]YBuffalo,\\\\\\\\n   New York [/wiki/Buffalo,_New_York], United States ([[Buffalo, New York]],\\\\\\\\n   United States)\\\\\\\\n   * If the smallest unit is an extant place, but the largest is not, it is\\\\\\\\n     preferable to space the links out when feasible, e.g. Kumrovec\\\\\\\\n     [/wiki/Kumrovec], then part of Austria-Hungary [/wiki/Austria-Hungary]\\\\\\\\n     ([[Kumrovec]], then part of [[Austria-Hungary]]).\\\\\\\\n * Linked text should avoid leading and trailing spaces. Punctuation, including\\\\\\\\n   spaces, should be external to the linked items.\\\\\\\\n * Articles on technical subjects might demand a higher density of links than\\\\\\\\n   general-interest articles, because they are likely to contain more technical\\\\\\\\n   terms that general dictionaries are unlikely to explain in context.\\\\\\\\n * Beware of linking to an article without first confirming that the target\\\\\\\\n   article covers the appropriate topic. For example, an article mentioning the\\\\\\\\n   physics unit \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"barn\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" should link to barn (unit) [/wiki/Barn_(unit)], not barn\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Barn].\\\\\\\\n * Shortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n    * MOS:DRAFTNOLINK\\\\\\\\n      [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:DRAFTNOLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\n   In articles, do not link to pages outside the article namespace\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:Namespace], including draft articles\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:DRAFT], except in articles about Wikipedia itself (and even\\\\\\\\n   in that case with care see Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Self-references to\\\\\\\\n   avoid [/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Self-references_to_avoid]).\\\\\\\\n * Do not unnecessarily make a reader chase links: if a highly technical term\\\\\\\\n   can be simply explained with very few words, do so.\\\\\\\\n * Shortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n    * MOS:NOFORCELINK\\\\\\\\n      [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:NOFORCELINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n    * MOS:FORCELINK\\\\\\\\n      [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:FORCELINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n   \\\\\\\\n   Use a link when appropriate, but as far as possible do not force a reader to\\\\\\\\n   use that link to understand the sentence. The text needs to make sense to\\\\\\\\n   readers who cannot follow links. Users may print articles or read offline,\\\\\\\\n   and Wikipedia content may be encountered in republished form\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:Reusing_Wikipedia_content], often without links.\\\\\\\\n * Refrain from implementing colored links [/wiki/Help:Link_color] that may\\\\\\\\n   impede user ability to distinguish links from regular text, or color links\\\\\\\\n   for purely aesthetic reasons.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOVERLINKING AND UNDERLINKING\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"WP:CONTEXT\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" redirects here. For context in the lead of a biography, see\\\\\\\\nMOS:CONTEXTBIO [/wiki/MOS:CONTEXTBIO]. For subject context in articles, see\\\\\\\\nWP:AUDIENCE [/wiki/Wikipedia:AUDIENCE].\\\\\\\\nFor notices that can be added to articles, see Template:Overlinked\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Template:Overlinked] and Template:Underlinked\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Template:Underlinked].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWHAT GENERALLY SHOULD BE LINKED\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"MOS:UL\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" redirects here. For unordered lists, see Wikipedia:Manual of\\\\\\\\nStyle/Lists Embedded lists\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lists#Embedded_lists]. For underlining, see\\\\\\\\nWikipedia:Manual of Style/Text formatting How not to apply emphasis\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Text_formatting#How_not_to_apply_emphasis].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:UL [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:UL&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:UNDERLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:UNDERLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAn article is said to be underlinked if unlinked words are needed to aid\\\\\\\\nunderstanding of the article. In general, links should be created for:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Relevant connections to the subject of another article that help readers\\\\\\\\n   understand the article more fully (see the example below). This can include\\\\\\\\n   people, events, and topics that already have an article or that clearly\\\\\\\\n   deserve one, as long as the link is relevant to the article in question.\\\\\\\\n * Articles with relevant information, for example: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"see Fourier series\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Fourier_series] for relevant background\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n * Articles explaining words of technical terms, jargon or slang expressions or\\\\\\\\n   phrasesbut you could also give a concise definition instead of or in\\\\\\\\n   addition to a link. If there is no appropriate Wikipedia article, an\\\\\\\\n   interwikimedia link [/wiki/Help:Interwikimedia_links] to Wiktionary\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wiktionary] could be used.\\\\\\\\n * Proper names [/wiki/Proper_name] that are likely to be unfamiliar to readers\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIf you feel that a link is relevant to the topic of the article but does not\\\\\\\\nbelong in the body of an article, consider moving it to a \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"See also\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" section\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout#See_also_section].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLinks may be created to potential articles that do not yet exist (see Red\\\\\\\\nlinks). If an article exists on a non-English language Wikipedia but not yet in\\\\\\\\nEnglish, consider a red link that also links to the non-English language article\\\\\\\\n(see Help:Interlanguage links Inline links\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Interlanguage_links#Inline_links]).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWHAT GENERALLY SHOULD NOT BE LINKED\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:OL [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:OL&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:OVERLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:OVERLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAn article is said to be overlinked if it contains an excessive number of links,\\\\\\\\nmaking it difficult to identify those likely to aid a reader's\\\\\\\\nunderstanding.[1][c] A good question to ask yourself is whether reading the\\\\\\\\narticle you're about to link to would help someone understand the article you\\\\\\\\nare linking from. Unless a term is particularly relevant to the context in the\\\\\\\\narticle, words and terms understood by most readers in context are usually not\\\\\\\\nlinked. Be conscious of your own demographic biases\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Systemic_bias] when determining whether certain terms have this\\\\\\\\nlevel of recognizability what is well known in your age group, line of work,\\\\\\\\nor country may be less so for others. Examples include:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Everyday words (e.g., education, violence, aircraft, river, animation)\\\\\\\\n * Common occupations (e.g., accountant, politician, actor)\\\\\\\\n * Common units of measurement, often those relating to time, temperature,\\\\\\\\n   length, area, or volume. If both non-metric and metric equivalents are given,\\\\\\\\n   as in 5 centimetres (2in), usually neither unit needs to be linked, because\\\\\\\\n   almost all readers understand at least one of the units.\\\\\\\\n * Dates (see Chronological items, below)\\\\\\\\n * Disambiguation [/wiki/Wikipedia:Disambiguation] pages should not be linked\\\\\\\\n   from articles unless the link is purposeful\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:Disambiguation#Links_to_disambiguation_pages], such as in a\\\\\\\\n   hatnote. Instead, use a piped link [/wiki/Wikipedia:Piped_link] to the\\\\\\\\n   appropriate article. For example, use Green tick\\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Green_check.svg/20px-Green_check.svg.png]Y[[Moana\\\\\\\\n   (character)|Moana]] for the Disney character, which appears as Moana\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Moana_(character)] and leads to the intended pageinstead of Red X\\\\\\\\n   [//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/ba/Red_x.svg/20px-Red_x.svg.png]N[[Moana]],\\\\\\\\n   which appears identical but leads to a disambiguation page.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn addition, major examples of the following categories should generally not be\\\\\\\\nlinked:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Countries (e.g., Brazil/Brazilian, Canada/Canadian, China/Chinese)\\\\\\\\n * Geographic features (e.g., the Himalayas, Pacific Ocean, South America)\\\\\\\\n * Settlements or municipalities (e.g., New Delhi; New York City, or just New\\\\\\\\n   York if the city context is already clear; London, if the context rules out\\\\\\\\n   London, Ontario [/wiki/London,_Ontario])\\\\\\\\n * Languages (e.g., English, Arabic, Korean, Spanish)\\\\\\\\n * Nationalities, ethnicities or identities (e.g., British, Japanese, Turkish,\\\\\\\\n   African American, Nigerian)\\\\\\\\n * Religions (e.g., Christianity, Islam, Hinduism, Buddhism)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLinks may be excessive even if they are informative. For example, because inline\\\\\\\\nlinks present relatively small tap targets on touchscreen devices, placing\\\\\\\\nseveral separate inline links close together within a section of text can make\\\\\\\\nnavigation more difficult for readers, especially if they have limited dexterity\\\\\\\\nor coordination. Balance readability, information, and accessibility when adding\\\\\\\\nmultiple links in one section of text. As of 2024, most stub articles average\\\\\\\\ntwo links per sentence, or about 10 to 20 links total. Most longer articles\\\\\\\\naverage somewhere around one link per 20 words. The lead of an article usually\\\\\\\\nhas a greater density of links than later parts of the article.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:CIRCULAR\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:CIRCULAR&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:CIRC [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:CIRC&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDo not link to pages that redirect back to the page\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Redirect#Self-redirects] the link is on (unless the link is to\\\\\\\\na redirect with possibilities [/wiki/Category:Redirects_with_possibilities] that\\\\\\\\nlinks to an appropriate section of the current article).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe purpose of linking is to clarify and to provide reasonable navigation\\\\\\\\nopportunities, not to emphasize a particular word. Do not link solely to draw\\\\\\\\nattention to certain words or ideas, or as a mark of respect.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nExternal links normally should not be placed in the body of an article (see\\\\\\\\nWikipedia:External links [/wiki/Wikipedia:External_links]).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDUPLICATE AND REPEAT LINKS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:REPEATLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:REPEATLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:LINKONCE\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:LINKONCE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:DUPLICATELINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:DUPLICATELINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:DUPLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:DUPLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:DL [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:DL&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:REFLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:REFLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * WP:LINKFIRST\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:LINKFIRST&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLink a term at most once per major section,[d] at first occurrence. Do not\\\\\\\\nre-link in other sections if not contextually important there. Other mentions\\\\\\\\nmay be linked if helpful, such as in infoboxes\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Infoboxes], tables\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Tables], image captions\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Captions], footnotes [/wiki/Help:Footnotes],\\\\\\\\nand hatnotes [/wiki/Wikipedia:Hatnote].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCitations [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources] stand alone in their usage, so there\\\\\\\\nis no problem with repeating the same link in many citations within an article;\\\\\\\\ne.g. |work=[[The Guardian]].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn glossaries [/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Glossaries], which are primarily\\\\\\\\nreferred to for encyclopedic entries on specific terms rather than read from top\\\\\\\\nto bottom like a regular article, it is usually desirable to repeat links\\\\\\\\n(including to other terms in the glossary) that were not already linked in the\\\\\\\\nsame entry (see Template:Glossary link [/wiki/Template:Glossary_link]).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDuplicate linking in stand-alone and embedded lists\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lists] is permissible if it significantly aids\\\\\\\\nthe reader. This is most often the case when the list is presenting information\\\\\\\\nthat could just as aptly be formatted in a table, and is expected to be parsed\\\\\\\\nfor particular bits of data, not read from top to bottom. If the list is normal\\\\\\\\narticle prose that happens to be formatted as a list, treat it as normal article\\\\\\\\nprose.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDuplicate links in an article can be found using the duplinks-alt\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/User:Evad37/duplinks-alt] sidebar tool.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLEAD SECTION\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:LEADLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:LEADLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFor links in the first sentence, see Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section\\\\\\\\nContextual links\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section#Contextual_links].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nToo many links can make the lead hard to read. In technical articles that use\\\\\\\\nuncommon terms, a higher-than-usual link density in the lead section\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section] may be necessary. In such cases,\\\\\\\\ntry to provide an informal explanation in the lead, avoiding using too many\\\\\\\\ntechnical terms until later in the article. (See Wikipedia:Make technical\\\\\\\\narticles understandable [/wiki/Wikipedia:Make_technical_articles_understandable]\\\\\\\\nand Wikipedia is not a scientific journal\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:What_Wikipedia_is_not#Wikipedia_is_not_a_manual,_guidebook,_textbook,_or_scientific_journal].)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMost Featured Articles [/wiki/Wikipedia:Featured_articles] contain about 12 to\\\\\\\\n25 links in the lead, with an average of about 1.5 links per sentence, or one\\\\\\\\nlink for every 16 words.[2]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAN EXAMPLE ARTICLE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:LE [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:LE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:LINKEXAMPLES\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:LINKEXAMPLES&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:EXAMPLELINKS\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:EXAMPLELINKS&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:COMMONWORDS\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:COMMONWORDS&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFor example, in the article on supply and demand [/wiki/Supply_and_demand]:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Almost certainly link \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"microeconomics [/wiki/Microeconomics]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"general\\\\\\\\n   equilibrium theory [/wiki/General_equilibrium_theory]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", as these are\\\\\\\\n   technical terms that many readers are unlikely to understand at first sight.\\\\\\\\n * Consider linking \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"price [/wiki/Price]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"goods [/wiki/Goods]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" only if\\\\\\\\n   these common words have technical dimensions that are specifically relevant\\\\\\\\n   to the topic.\\\\\\\\n * Do not link to the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"United States\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", because that is an article on a very\\\\\\\\n   broad topic with no direct connection to supply and demand.\\\\\\\\n * Definitely do not link \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"wheat\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", because it is a common term with no\\\\\\\\n   particular relationship to the article on supply and demand, beyond its\\\\\\\\n   arbitrary use as an example of traded goods in that article.\\\\\\\\n * Make sure that the links are directed to the correct articles: in this\\\\\\\\n   example, you should link goods [/wiki/Goods], not good [/wiki/Good], which\\\\\\\\n   goes to a page on the philosophical concept. Many common dictionary words are\\\\\\\\n   ambiguous terms in Wikipedia and linking to them is often unhelpful to\\\\\\\\n   readers; \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Good\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" is a surname and the name of albums, companies, etc., and the\\\\\\\\n   article title Good (disambiguation) [/wiki/Good_(disambiguation)] is used to\\\\\\\\n   index those.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLINK CLARITY\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:LINKCLARITY\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:LINKCLARITY&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe article linked to should correspond as closely as possible to the term\\\\\\\\nshowing as the link, given the context.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFor example, a link to the article Requiem (Mozart) [/wiki/Requiem_(Mozart)]\\\\\\\\nshould be clear that it is Mozart's Requiem in particular, rather than requiems\\\\\\\\nin general. The link target and the link label do not have to match exactly, but\\\\\\\\nthe link must be as intuitive as possible (see Intuitiveness).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nArticle textWikitext [/wiki/Help:Wikitext]Notecheck\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/20px-Yes_check.svg.png]YWhen\\\\\\\\nMozart wrote his Requiem [/wiki/Requiem_(Mozart)]When Mozart wrote [[Requiem\\\\\\\\n(Mozart)|his Requiem]]Includes the word \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"his\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" to specify\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/X_mark.svg/20px-X_mark.svg.png]NWhen\\\\\\\\nMozart wrote his Requiem [/wiki/Requiem_(Mozart)]When Mozart wrote his [[Requiem\\\\\\\\n(Mozart)|Requiem]]Only word \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Requiem\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"check\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/20px-Yes_check.svg.png]YPrevin\\\\\\\\nconducted Mozart's Requiem [/wiki/Requiem_(Mozart)]Previn conducted [[Requiem\\\\\\\\n(Mozart)|Mozart's Requiem]]\\\\\\\\nor Previn conducted [[Mozart's Requiem]]Specifying that it is \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Mozart's\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/X_mark.svg/20px-X_mark.svg.png]NPrevin\\\\\\\\nconducted Mozart's Requiem [/wiki/Requiem_(Mozart)]Previn conducted Mozart's\\\\\\\\n[[Requiem (Mozart)|Requiem]]Only word \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Requiem\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLINK SPECIFICITY\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:SPECIFICLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:SPECIFICLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAlways link to the article on the most specific topic appropriate to the context\\\\\\\\nfrom which you link: it generally contains more focused information, as well as\\\\\\\\nlinks to more general topics.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWhat you typeHow it appearsSpecificity[[Icelandic orthography]]Icelandic\\\\\\\\northography [/wiki/Icelandic_orthography]Specific (preferred)[[Icelandic\\\\\\\\nlanguage|Icelandic]] orthographyIcelandic [/wiki/Icelandic_language]\\\\\\\\northographyRelated but less specificIcelandic [[orthography]]Icelandic\\\\\\\\northography [/wiki/Orthography]Unspecificthe [[flag of Tokelau]]the flag of\\\\\\\\nTokelau [/wiki/Flag_of_Tokelau]Specific (preferred)the [[flag]] of\\\\\\\\n[[Tokelau]]the flag [/wiki/Flag] of Tokelau [/wiki/Tokelau]Unspecific[[Requiem\\\\\\\\n(Mozart)|Requiem]]Requiem [/wiki/Requiem_(Mozart)]Specific\\\\\\\\n(preferred)[[Requiem]]Requiem [/wiki/Requiem]Unspecific\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIf there is no article about the most specific topic, do one of the following\\\\\\\\nthings:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Consider creating the article [/wiki/Wikipedia:Starting_an_article] yourself.\\\\\\\\n * If an article on the specific topic does not yet exist, create a redirect\\\\\\\\n   page to the article about a more general topic, as described in section\\\\\\\\n   Redirects. For example, if no article yet exists on the song \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Sad Statue\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n   from the album Mezmerize, create a new article called Sad Statue\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Sad_Statue] that is a redirect to the article Mezmerize\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Mezmerize_(album)].\\\\\\\\n * If there is no article on a more general topic either, then create a red link\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:RED], but first, read Red links below.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWhen neither a redirect nor a red link appears appropriate, consider linking to\\\\\\\\na more general article instead.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFor example, instead of\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/X_mark.svg/20px-X_mark.svg.png]NBaroque\\\\\\\\nhairstyles [/w/index.php?title=Baroque_hairstyles&action=edit&redlink=1] (an\\\\\\\\narticle which, as of 2023, had never been created),\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nwrite\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\ncheck\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/20px-Yes_check.svg.png]YBaroque\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Baroque] hairstyles (which provides a link to the Baroque era),\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\ncheck\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/20px-Yes_check.svg.png]YBaroque\\\\\\\\nhairstyles [/wiki/Hairstyle] (which provides a link to the article on\\\\\\\\nhairstyle),\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\ncheck\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/20px-Yes_check.svg.png]YBaroque\\\\\\\\nhairstyles (which provides no link at all, and which may be preferable depending\\\\\\\\non context),\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nor\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\ncheck\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fb/Yes_check.svg/20px-Yes_check.svg.png]Yhairstyles\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Hairstyle] of the Baroque [/wiki/Baroque] (which provides separate links\\\\\\\\nto both topics);\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nhowever, do not create\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/X_mark.svg/20px-X_mark.svg.png]NBaroque\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Baroque] hairstyles [/wiki/Hairstyle] as two adjacent links because they\\\\\\\\nmay be misinterpreted as linking to a single article on that topic.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSECTION LINKS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:SECTIONLINKS\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:SECTIONLINKS&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:SECLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:SECLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:SL [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:SL&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFurther information: Help:Link Section linking (anchors)\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Link#Section_linking_(anchors)], and Help:Section Section linking\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Section#Section_linking]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIf an existing article has a section specifically about a topic, linking to that\\\\\\\\nsection takes the reader directly to the relevant information. Section-linking\\\\\\\\noptions are piped links [/wiki/MOS:SECTLINK], redirects [/wiki/MOS:SECTLINK],\\\\\\\\nand the {{Section link [/wiki/Template:Section_link]}} template, which also\\\\\\\\ngenerates the  character.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAVOIDING BROKEN SECTION LINKS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:RENAMESECTION\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:RENAMESECTION&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:BROKENSECTIONLINKS\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:BROKENSECTIONLINKS&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA problem can arise if the title of the section is changed for any reason,\\\\\\\\nbecause this action breaks any incoming section links or excerpts\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Template:Excerpt]. (If this occurs, incoming links default to the top of\\\\\\\\nthe linked article.) The recommended way [/wiki/Wikipedia:TARGET] to prevent\\\\\\\\nthis breakage is to use a {{subst:Anchor [/wiki/Template:Anchor]}} template\\\\\\\\nspecifying the section's prior name.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:HIDDENLINKADVICE\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:HIDDENLINKADVICE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAn alternative, supplementary method has been to add a hidden comment to the\\\\\\\\ntarget section such as <!-- \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Quark\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" links here -->[e] so that someone changing\\\\\\\\nthe title of that section can fix the incoming links. This method is weaker,\\\\\\\\nsince it puts the workload on the editor seeking to change the section title.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThere are some bots aimed to fix broken anchors: cewbot\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/User:Cewbot/log/20201008/configuration], Dexbot [/wiki/User:Dexbot], and\\\\\\\\nFrescoBot [/wiki/User:FrescoBot].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nTECHNIQUES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nREDIRECTS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:RDR [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:RDR&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:REDIR [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:REDIR&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMain page: Wikipedia:Redirect [/wiki/Wikipedia:Redirect]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSuppose you need to link poodle, and there is no such article yet. You might\\\\\\\\nwant to create a redirect from \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"poodle\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" to \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"dog\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" as follows: Link as usual: She\\\\\\\\nowned a [[poodle]]. When you save or preview this, you see: She owned a poodle\\\\\\\\n[/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:Red_link_example&action=edit&redlink=1]. Follow\\\\\\\\nthe red link, and you are invited to create a new page for poodle; enter\\\\\\\\n(perhaps) #REDIRECT [[Dog]], so that readers clicking on poodle are taken, for\\\\\\\\nnow, to the dog article.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe redirect is better in a case like this than a direct link like\\\\\\\\n[[dog|poodle]], because when an actual poodle article is eventually created\\\\\\\\n(replacing the redirect), readers following the poodle link are taken there\\\\\\\\nautomatically without anyone needing to review all the links to dog to see which\\\\\\\\nones should actually go to poodle.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nTo link to a redirect page without following the underlying redirect, use e.g.\\\\\\\\n{{no redirect|poodle}}.Avoid linking redirects that are self links\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Self_link] (WP:SELFRED [/wiki/Wikipedia:SELFRED]).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPIPED LINKS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:PIPE [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:PIPE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:PIPEDLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:PIPEDLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFurther information: Wikipedia:Piped link [/wiki/Wikipedia:Piped_link]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThough a wikilink defaults to displaying the title of the target article, it is\\\\\\\\npossible to choose more specific or more appropriate display text for the\\\\\\\\nintended context. This can be done with the use of the pipe character (|). For\\\\\\\\nexample, [[Henry II of England|Henry II]] displays as Henry II\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Henry_II_of_England].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSTYLE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:PIPESTYLE\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:PIPESTYLE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Plurals and other derived names. [[apple]]s displays as apples [/wiki/Apple],\\\\\\\\n   and this is simpler and clearer than [[apple|apples]]. Similarly:\\\\\\\\n   [[appeal]]ing, [[hyperlink]]ed, [[red]]dest. Some characters do not work\\\\\\\\n   after the link; see Help:Link [/wiki/Help:Link] for more details.\\\\\\\\n * Case sensitivity. Links are not sensitive to initial capitalization, so there\\\\\\\\n   is no need to use the pipe character where the case of the initial letter is\\\\\\\\n   the only difference between the link text and the target page. (Wikipedia\\\\\\\\n   article titles almost always begin with a capital, whereas the linked words\\\\\\\\n   in context often do not.) However, links are case-sensitive for all\\\\\\\\n   characters after the initial one.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nINTUITIVENESS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"MOS:EGG\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" redirects here. You may also be looking for WP:EASTEREGG\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:EASTEREGG].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:EGG [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:EGG&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:EASTEREGG\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:EASTEREGG&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:SUBMARINE\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:SUBMARINE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nyoung child looks under some green plants\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Easter_egg_hunt.JPG/250px-Easter_egg_hunt.JPG]/wiki/File:Easter_egg_hunt.JPGIs\\\\\\\\nthere anything hidden in here?\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nKeep piped links as intuitive as possible. Per the principle of least\\\\\\\\nastonishment [/wiki/Wikipedia:Principle_of_least_astonishment], make sure that\\\\\\\\nthe reader knows what to expect when following a link. You should plan your page\\\\\\\\nstructure and links so that everything appears reasonable and makes sense.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA link's visible label does not need to match the exact title of the article\\\\\\\\nbeing linked, such as in [[surgical suture|suture]] or [[Passing (sports)|passed\\\\\\\\nthe ball]]. However, avoid \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Easter egg [/wiki/Easter_egg_(media)]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" or\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"submarine\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" links, which are links that unexpectedly hide relevant information\\\\\\\\nunderneath the link's label. For example, do not write:\\\\\\\\n  Richard Feynman was also known for work in [[Parton (particle\\\\\\\\nphysics)|particle physics]].\\\\\\\\nHere readers would see the link displayed as particle physics\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Parton_(particle_physics)], not the hidden reference to the page Parton\\\\\\\\n(particle physics) [/wiki/Parton_(particle_physics)], unless they followed the\\\\\\\\nlink or inspected the target title e.g. by mousing over [/wiki/Mouseover] it. If\\\\\\\\na physical copy of the article were printed, or the article saved as an audio\\\\\\\\nfile, the reference to the parton model would be lost.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nInstead, refer to the separate article with an explicit see also X, or by\\\\\\\\nrephrasing the sentence, as in:\\\\\\\\n  Richard Feynman was also known for work in [[particle physics]], especially\\\\\\\\nthe [[Parton (particle physics)|parton]] model.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMORE WORDS INTO A LINK\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:MORELINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:MORELINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:MORELINKWORDS\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:MORELINKWORDS&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSometimes moving other words into the bluelinked text avoids surprise.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFor example, in an article on the history of Texas:\\\\\\\\n  In 1845, the Republic of Texas was [[Texas annexation|annexed]] by the\\\\\\\\nUnited States.\\\\\\\\nappears as:\\\\\\\\n  In 1845, the Republic of Texas was annexed [/wiki/Texas_annexation] by the\\\\\\\\nUnited States.\\\\\\\\nwhich looks the same as a link to the generic topic of annexation\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Annexation] would.\\\\\\\\nHowever:\\\\\\\\n  In 1845, the [[Texas annexation|Republic of Texas was annexed]] by the\\\\\\\\nUnited States.\\\\\\\\nappears as:\\\\\\\\n  In 1845, the Republic of Texas was annexed [/wiki/Texas_annexation] by the\\\\\\\\nUnited States.\\\\\\\\nand is clear that the 1845 annexation of Texas is linked.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nNAMES IN NAMES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:LINKINNAME\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:LINKINNAME&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:PARTIALNAMELINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:PARTIALNAMELINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDo not place a link to a name within another name. For example:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWrite:[[Columbus Avenue (Boston)|Columbus Avenue]] Columbus Avenue\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Columbus_Avenue_(Boston)]Do not write:[[Christopher Columbus|Columbus]]\\\\\\\\nAvenue Columbus [/wiki/Christopher_Columbus] AvenueWrite:[[Feynman diagram]]\\\\\\\\nFeynman diagram [/wiki/Feynman_diagram]Do not write:[[Richard Feynman|Feynman]]\\\\\\\\ndiagram Feynman [/wiki/Richard_Feynman] diagram\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe above applies regardless of whether linking to the full name creates a red\\\\\\\\nlink [/wiki/Wikipedia:Red_link]; for example, even if there is no article titled\\\\\\\\nLafayette Avenue (Brooklyn)\\\\\\\\n[/w/index.php?title=Lafayette_Avenue_(Brooklyn)&action=edit&redlink=1]:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nDo not write:[[Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette|Lafayette]] Avenue\\\\\\\\nLafayette [/wiki/Gilbert_du_Motier,_Marquis_de_Lafayette] Avenue\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSee also Link clarity.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPIPING AND REDIRECTS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:NOPIPE\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:NOPIPE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:DYKPIPE\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:DYKPIPE&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPer WP:NOTBROKEN [/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTBROKEN] and Link specificity above, do\\\\\\\\nnot use a piped link where it is possible to use a redirected term that fits\\\\\\\\nwell within the scope of the text. For example, the page Papageno\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Papageno] is a redirect to the article about Mozart's opera The Magic\\\\\\\\nFlute [/wiki/The_Magic_Flute] (since Papageno is a character in The Magic\\\\\\\\nFlute). While editing some other article, you might want to link the term\\\\\\\\nPapageno; here, you might be tempted to avoid the redirect by using a pipe\\\\\\\\nwithin the link, as in [[The Magic Flute|Papageno]]. Instead, write simply\\\\\\\\n[[Papageno]] and let the system handle the rest. This has two advantages: first,\\\\\\\\nif an article is written later about the more specific subject (in this case,\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Papageno\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", the character), fewer links need to be changed to accommodate the\\\\\\\\nnew article; second, it indicates that the article is wanted\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Most-wanted_articles].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAn exception to this rule is when linking to articles in Did you know\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Did_you_know] (DYK) \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"hooks\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Did_you_know#DYK_rules]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" on the Main Page\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Main_Page#mp-dyk-h2], where piping links to prevent readers from seeing a\\\\\\\\nredirect notice is preferable, and the hook is live only for a short time. (See\\\\\\\\nalso WP:Piped link When not to use\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Piped_link#When_not_to_use].)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPIPED LINKS AND REDIRECTS TO SECTIONS OF ARTICLES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:SECTLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:SECTLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFurther information: Section links, Help:Link Section linking (anchors)\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Link#Section_linking_(anchors)], and Wikipedia:Redirect Targeted\\\\\\\\nand untargeted redirects\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Redirect#Targeted_and_untargeted_redirects]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAs explained above [/wiki/MOS:SECLINK], links to sections can take the reader\\\\\\\\ndirectly to relevant information.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPIPED LINKS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFurther information: Wikipedia:Piped link [/wiki/Wikipedia:Piped_link]\\\\\\\\nSee also: Template:Anchor [/wiki/Template:Anchor]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nUsing piped links to sections avoids the unsightly Article#Section name in the\\\\\\\\ndisplay text.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe format for a piped link is [[Article#Section|name of link]]. For example, to\\\\\\\\nlink to the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Culture\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" subsection of the article Oman [/wiki/Oman], type:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[[Oman#Culture|culture of Oman]],\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nwhich displays as culture of Oman [/wiki/Oman#Culture]. The section name is\\\\\\\\ncase-sensitive, unlike article titles which are case insensitive.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFinally, consider adding a hidden comment [/wiki/MOS:COMMENT] to the target\\\\\\\\nsection so that future editors who edit the title of that section know they must\\\\\\\\nsearch for and fix all incoming links [/wiki/Incoming_links], for example:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n<!-- The article ArticleName links to this section. Should the section's title\\\\\\\\nchange, fix now mistargeted wikilinks, or use the {{subst:Anchor|}} template to\\\\\\\\ncreate an anchor to keep the stability of external incoming links too. -->\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nA list of incoming wikilinks can be generated using the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"What links here\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:What_links_here]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" feature. As a general rule, it is preferable,\\\\\\\\nparticularly in cases where a section has a large number of backlinks, to use\\\\\\\\n{{subst:Anchor [/wiki/Template:Anchor]}} in the HTML element of the header.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nTo link to a section within the same article, one can simply prefix the name of\\\\\\\\nthe section header with the pound sign (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"#\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\") nested in square brackets, for\\\\\\\\nexample (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"#\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"):\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[[#Promotion to rook or bishop| promotion to a rook or bishop]].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPrefix the label of a wikilink that targets a section header with the section\\\\\\\\nsymbol (\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\").\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nREDIRECTS TO SECTIONS WHICH MAY BECOME ARTICLES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMany topics useful for linking may currently appear only as sections of other\\\\\\\\nWikipedia articles, but are potentially notable enough to become articles on\\\\\\\\ntheir own. For example, the article Eastern Anyshire might have a small\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"History\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" section, but this does not prevent the article History of Eastern\\\\\\\\nAnyshire being written eventually. A redirect [/wiki/Wikipedia:Redirect] page\\\\\\\\nfrom such a sub-topic to a general topic may exist already; if not, a redirect\\\\\\\\ncan be created when the occasion arises. It is bad practice to create links in\\\\\\\\narticle text using the format [[Article#Section]]; navigation then becomes\\\\\\\\ndifficult if the section is expanded into a new article. Instead, link using a\\\\\\\\nredirect to the main topic; it costs little [/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTBROKEN] and\\\\\\\\nmakes improvements easier. Thus:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * In a redirect page named \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"HistoryofTopic\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", use #REDIRECT [[Topic#History]].\\\\\\\\n * In another article, use [[history of Topic]].\\\\\\\\n * Avoid: [[Topic#History|history of Topic]].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLINKS TO NON-ENGLISH LANGUAGE PAGES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSee Help:Interlanguage links Inline links\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Help:Interlanguage_links#Inline_links].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLINKS TO WIKIPEDIA'S CATEGORIES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSee also: Wikipedia:Colon trick [/wiki/Wikipedia:Colon_trick]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWikipedia has categories of articles; for example, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Phrases\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". Adding the\\\\\\\\nwikitext [[Category:Phrases]] to an article will add that article to the\\\\\\\\ncategory \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Phrases\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". (This will not create any visible addition to the body text\\\\\\\\nof the article.)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIf you instead want to create a visible link to a category, add a colon in front\\\\\\\\nof the word \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Category\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". For example, [[:Category:Phrases]] creates the link\\\\\\\\nCategory:Phrases [/wiki/Category:Phrases]. As with other links, piping can be\\\\\\\\nused: Phrases [/wiki/Category:Phrases].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe {{See also cat [/wiki/Template:See_also_cat]}} template can be used instead:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n{{See also cat|Phrases}} creates:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSee also: Category:Phrases [/wiki/Category:Phrases]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nRED LINKS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:REDLINKS\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:REDLINKS&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:REDLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:REDLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:RL [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:RL&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMain page: Wikipedia:Red link [/wiki/Wikipedia:Red_link]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOverlinking in general is a style issue partly because of the undesirable effect\\\\\\\\non readability. But if too many blue links are distracting, a red link is even\\\\\\\\nmore so. The unassuming coloration of the text (probably black) is the most\\\\\\\\nproductive.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn prose, if it seems that the level of red linking is overlinking, remember\\\\\\\\nthat red links have been found to be a driving force that encourages\\\\\\\\ncontributions,[f] and then use that fact to balance the perceived stylistic\\\\\\\\nissues of \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"overlinking\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" the red links.(Legitimate red links are titles to\\\\\\\\nunfulfilled coverage of topics that do not violate \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"What Wikipedia is not\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:What_Wikipedia_is_not]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" policy.) Given a certain number of red\\\\\\\\nlinks needed, if marking all of them could be overlinking, then just how many\\\\\\\\nshould be marked could be a style issue, and just which ones are priority is a\\\\\\\\nhelpful contribution.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn lists [/wiki/MOS:LISTS], overlinking red links can occur when every item on a\\\\\\\\nlist is a red link. If the list is uniform, where each item clearly qualifies\\\\\\\\nfor an article, a single red link (or blue link) could indicate that. If the\\\\\\\\nlist is not uniform, the research effort to mark all possible red links is a\\\\\\\\nrisky investment: while red means \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"approved\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" status, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"black\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" remains ambiguous,\\\\\\\\neven though it meant \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"disapproved\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" after research. Valid requests\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Requested_articles] for the future creation of each title in a\\\\\\\\nlist, or in prose, may also be a risky investment when the number of red links\\\\\\\\ncould be perceived by other editors as overlinking, and then removed before the\\\\\\\\ninvestment was fruitful. The removal of massive numbers of red links from an\\\\\\\\noverlinked list is best handled by an editor skilled in the automation of text\\\\\\\\nprocessing [/wiki/Text_processing].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nRed links can also be removed if they violate policy or the guideline for red\\\\\\\\nlinks [/wiki/Wikipedia:Red_link], but otherwise red links do not have an\\\\\\\\nexpiration date. If you remain convinced there is overlinking of red links,\\\\\\\\nconsider turning some of them blue. The methods to do so are by creating a\\\\\\\\nsimple stub [/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub], a redirect [/wiki/Wikipedia:Redirect], or a\\\\\\\\ndisambiguation [/wiki/Wikipedia:Disambiguation] page. All of these require the\\\\\\\\ncertainty that the red link was legitimate in the first place, such as the\\\\\\\\nconventions on article titles [/wiki/Wikipedia:Article_titles].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCOLORED LINKS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMain page: Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Text formatting Color\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Text_formatting#Color]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn prose refrain from implementing colored links, as these may impede users'\\\\\\\\nability to distinguish links from regular text. See the guides to editing\\\\\\\\narticles for accessibility at contrast [/wiki/Wikipedia:CONTRAST] and navbox\\\\\\\\ncolors [/wiki/Wikipedia:NAVBOXCOLOUR].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCHECKING LINKS AS THEY ARE CREATED\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * WP:TESTLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:TESTLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIt's easy to create an erroneous link without realizing it. When adding a new\\\\\\\\nlink, it's a good idea to use the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Show preview\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" button and then (from the\\\\\\\\npreview) open the link in a new browser tab to check that it goes where you\\\\\\\\nintend.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nBy following naming conventions [/wiki/Wikipedia:Naming_conventions], an\\\\\\\\ninternal link is much more likely to lead to an existing article. When there is\\\\\\\\nnot yet an article about the subject, a good link makes it easier to create a\\\\\\\\ncorrectly named article later.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSPECIFIC CASES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLINKING MONTH-AND-DAY OR YEAR\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * WP:DATELINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:DATELINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * WP:YEARLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:YEARLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * WP:LINKYEAR\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia:LINKYEAR&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMonth-and-day articles (e.g. February24 [/wiki/February_24] and 10July\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/July_10]) and year articles (e.g. 1795 [/wiki/1795], 1955 [/wiki/1955],\\\\\\\\n2007 [/wiki/2007]) should not be linked unless the linked date or year has a\\\\\\\\nsignificant connection to the subject of the linking article, beyond that of the\\\\\\\\ndate itself, so that the linking enhances the reader's understanding of the\\\\\\\\nsubject.For example:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * The date (or year) should not be linked in a sentence such as (from Sydney\\\\\\\\n   Opera House [/wiki/Sydney_Opera_House]): \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"The Sydney Opera House was made a\\\\\\\\n   UNESCO World Heritage Site on 28 June 2007\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\", because little if any content of\\\\\\\\n   either June28 [/wiki/June_28] or 2007 [/wiki/2007] pertains to either\\\\\\\\n   UNESCO, World Heritage Sites, or the Sydney Opera House.\\\\\\\\n * The years of birth and death of architect Philip Johnson\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Philip_Johnson] should not be linked, because little if any content of\\\\\\\\n   1906 [/wiki/1906] or 2005 [/wiki/2005] enhances the reader's understanding of\\\\\\\\n   Johnson or his work.\\\\\\\\n * [[Timeline of World War II (1942)|1942]] might be linked from another article\\\\\\\\n   about WWII.\\\\\\\\n * [[1787 in science|1787]] might be linked from a passage discussing a\\\\\\\\n   particular development in the metric system which occurred in that year.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nHowever, in intrinsically chronological articles (1789 [/wiki/1789], January\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/January], and 1940s [/wiki/1940s]), links to specific month-and-day,\\\\\\\\nmonth-and year, or year articles are not discouraged.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCommemorative days (Saint Patrick's Day [/wiki/Saint_Patrick%27s_Day]) are not\\\\\\\\nconsidered month-and-day items for the purposes of the above.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nUNITS OF MEASUREMENT THAT ARE NOT OBSCURE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nGenerally, a unit should be linked only if it is likely to be obscure to many\\\\\\\\nreaders or is itself being discussed. For example, the troy ounce\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Troy_ounce], bushel [/wiki/Bushel], hand [/wiki/Hand_(unit)], candela\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Candela], knot [/wiki/Knot_(unit)], mho [/wiki/Mho], or millibarn\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Millibarn] might be considered obscure even if they are well-known within\\\\\\\\ntheir field of use. Other units may be obscure in some countries even if well\\\\\\\\nknown in others.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEXTERNAL LINKS SECTION\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMain page: Wikipedia:External links [/wiki/Wikipedia:External_links]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWikipedia is not a link collection, and an article comprising only links is\\\\\\\\ncontrary to what the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"what Wikipedia is not\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" policy [/wiki/Wikipedia:NOT#LINKS]\\\\\\\\ndictates.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSYNTAX\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe syntax for referencing a web address is simple. Just enclose it in single\\\\\\\\nbrackets with a space between the URL and the text that is displayed when the\\\\\\\\npage is previewed or saved:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[https://www.example.org Text to display]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe text appears as:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nText to display [https://www.example.org]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe URL must begin with either http:// or https:// (preferring https://, where\\\\\\\\navailable), or another common protocol, such as ftp:// or news://. If no\\\\\\\\nprotocol is used, the square brackets display normally [like this] and can\\\\\\\\nbe used in the standard way.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIn addition, putting URLs in plain text with no markup automatically produces a\\\\\\\\nlink, for example https://www.example.org/  https://www.example.org/\\\\\\\\n[https://www.example.org/]. However, this feature may disappear in a future\\\\\\\\nrelease. Therefore, in cases where you wish to display the URL because it is\\\\\\\\nintrinsically valuable information, it is better to use the short form of the\\\\\\\\nURL (domain name) as the optional text: [https://www.example.org/ example.org]\\\\\\\\nproduces example.org [https://www.example.org/].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nCitations templates [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_templates] such as {{cite web\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Template:Cite_web]}} should not be used in the ==External links==\\\\\\\\nsection. External link templates [/wiki/Category:External_link_templates] such\\\\\\\\nas {{official website [/wiki/Template:Official_website]}} are used instead of\\\\\\\\ncitation templates.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLINK TITLES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMain page: Wikipedia:Embedded citations [/wiki/Wikipedia:Embedded_citations]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEmbedded HTML links within an article are a now-deprecated way to supply a bare\\\\\\\\nURL as a source within an article, by simply enclosing the URL in square\\\\\\\\nbrackets, like this:\\\\\\\\n[https://www.guardian.co.uk/usa/story/0,12271,1650417,00.html]  [1]\\\\\\\\n[https://www.guardian.co.uk/usa/story/0,12271,1650417,00.html]. However, you\\\\\\\\nshould add a descriptive title when an external link is offered in the\\\\\\\\nReferences [/wiki/MOS:REFERENCES], Further reading [/wiki/MOS:FURTHER], or\\\\\\\\nExternal links [/wiki/Wikipedia:EL] sections. This is done by supplying\\\\\\\\ndescriptive text after the URL, separated by a space and enclosing it all in\\\\\\\\nsquare brackets.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFor example, to add a title to a bare URL such as https://en.wikipedia.org/\\\\\\\\n(this is rendered as https://en.wikipedia.org/ [https://en.wikipedia.org/]), use\\\\\\\\nthe following syntax: [https://en.wikipedia.org/ an open-content encyclopedia]\\\\\\\\n(this is rendered as \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"an open-content encyclopedia\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\").\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:URL [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:URL&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:DOMAINNAME\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:DOMAINNAME&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nGenerally, URLs and domain names are ugly and uninformative; it is better for a\\\\\\\\nmeaningful title or description to be displayed rather than the URL or domain\\\\\\\\nitself. For example, European Space Agency website [http://www.esa.int/ESA] is\\\\\\\\nmuch more reader-friendly than http://www.esa.int/ESA [http://www.esa.int/ESA].\\\\\\\\nThere may be exceptions where the domain name is well known or is also the\\\\\\\\ncompany or publication name. When a URL or domain name is given, putting both a\\\\\\\\nplain-English title or description and the URL is often more informative: for\\\\\\\\nexample, European Space Agency website, www.esa.int [http://www.esa.int/ESA].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIf the URL or domain name is displayed, make it as simple as possible; for\\\\\\\\nexample, if the index.html is superfluous, remove it (but be sure to check in\\\\\\\\npreview mode first). Many but not all sites can be trimmed of a leading \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"www.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\";\\\\\\\\ntest it to be sure. Use camel case [/wiki/Camel_case] to make a displayed domain\\\\\\\\nmore readable, e.g. WashingtonPost.com versus washingtonpost.com.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"printable version\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" of a Wikipedia article displays all URLs in full,\\\\\\\\nincluding those given a title, so no information is lost.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nURLS AS EMBEDDED (NUMBERED) LINKS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWithout the optional text, external references appear as automatically numbered\\\\\\\\nlinks: For example,\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nis displayed like this:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[2] [https://en.wikipedia.org/]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nNumbered links of this type used to be used after the punctuation, like this,[3]\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:CITE] with a full citation given in the\\\\\\\\nReferences section. This style of referencing is now deprecated, because such\\\\\\\\nlinks are susceptible to link rot [/wiki/Wikipedia:Link_rot]. See\\\\\\\\nWikipedia:Citing sources [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources] and\\\\\\\\nWikipedia:Verifiability [/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability] for more information.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nPOSITION IN ARTICLE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMain page: MOS:ORDER [/wiki/MOS:ORDER]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nEmbedded links that support information in an article are positioned in the same\\\\\\\\nmanner as any other reference in the article, following the usual standards\\\\\\\\nabout citation formatting [/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources#Embedded_links] and\\\\\\\\nplacement in relation to punctuation [/wiki/Wikipedia:REFPUNC].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLinks that are not used as sources can be listed in the External links section,\\\\\\\\nlike this:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n==External links==* [https://...] * [http://...]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAs with other top-level headings, two equal signs should be used to mark up the\\\\\\\\nexternal links heading (see Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Layout Headings\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout#Headings]). External links should always\\\\\\\\nbe the last section in an article. It precedes categories and some kinds of\\\\\\\\nnavigation templates [/wiki/Wikipedia:NAVBOX].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIf there is a dispute on the position of an embedded link, consider organizing\\\\\\\\nalphabetically.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nNON-ENGLISH-LANGUAGE SITES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWebpages in English are highly preferred. Linking to non-English pages may still\\\\\\\\nbe useful for readers in the following cases:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * When the website is the subject of the article\\\\\\\\n * When linking to pages with maps, diagrams, photos, tables (explain the key\\\\\\\\n   terms with the link, so that people who do not know the language can\\\\\\\\n   interpret them)\\\\\\\\n * When the webpage contains information found on no English-language site of\\\\\\\\n   comparable quality, and is used as a citation (or when translations on\\\\\\\\n   English-language sites are not authoritative).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIf the language is one that most readers could not be expected to recognize, or\\\\\\\\nis for some other reason unclear from the name of the publication or the book or\\\\\\\\narticle or page title, consider indicating what language the site is in.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Example: Koha Jon [http://www.kohajone.com/], an Albanian-language newspaper\\\\\\\\n   from Tirana [/wiki/Tirana]\\\\\\\\n * Example: El Pas [https://www.elpais.es/], a Spanish-language newspaper from\\\\\\\\n   Madrid [/wiki/Madrid]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nYou can also indicate the language by putting a language template after the\\\\\\\\nlink. This is done using Template:In lang [/wiki/Template:In_lang] by typing\\\\\\\\n{{In lang [/wiki/Template:In_lang]|<language code>}}. For example, {{In lang\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Template:In_lang]|es}} displays as: (in Spanish). See list of ISO 639\\\\\\\\ncodes [/wiki/List_of_ISO_639_codes].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nWhen using one of the Citation Style 1 [/wiki/Help:Citation_Style_1] or Citation\\\\\\\\nStyle 2 [/wiki/Help:Citation_Style_2] templates, instead of the {{In lang}}\\\\\\\\ntemplate, use the |language= parameter. This parameter accepts language names or\\\\\\\\nlanguage codes; see this list of supported names and codes\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Template:Citation_Style_documentation/language/doc]. (Use of language\\\\\\\\ncodes is to be preferred because cs1|2 automatically renders language names in\\\\\\\\nthe language of the local Wikipedia.)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFILE TYPE AND SIZE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIf the link is not to an HTML [/wiki/HTML] or PDF [/wiki/PDF] file (the latter\\\\\\\\nis identified automatically by the software with an icon like this: [4]\\\\\\\\n[https://www.example.com/test.pdf]), identify the file type. Useful templates\\\\\\\\nare available: {{DOClink [/wiki/Template:DOClink]}}, {{RTFlink\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Template:RTFlink]}}. If a browser plugin [/wiki/Browser_plugin] is\\\\\\\\nrequired to view the file, mention that as well. If a link is to a PDF file but\\\\\\\\ndoesn't end with .pdf, you can put a #.pdf at the end to flag it as a PDF.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIf the link is to a very large page (considering all its elements, including\\\\\\\\nimages), a note about that is useful since someone with a slow or expensive\\\\\\\\nconnection may decide not to visit it.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nINTERWIKI LINKS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcuts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:IWL [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:IWL&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:INTERWIKI\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:INTERWIKI&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:INTERLINK\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:INTERLINK&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nMain pages: Help:Interlanguage links [/wiki/Help:Interlanguage_links] and\\\\\\\\nHelp:Interwiki linking [/wiki/Help:Interwiki_linking]\\\\\\\\nFurther information: Wikipedia:Wikimedia sister projects\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikimedia_sister_projects]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLINKING\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nUsing links to wiktionary [/wiki/Wiktionary] as an example, interwiki links can\\\\\\\\ntake the form of:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[[wikt:article]] which appears as: wikt:article\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/article]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe pipe symbol suppresses the prefix:\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[[wikt:article|]]  article [https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/article]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nAdding text after the pipe allows either the same or a different text (with no\\\\\\\\nprefix):\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[[wikt:article|article]]  article\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/article][[wikt:article|Any text]]  Any text\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/article]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nTo avoid reader confusion, inline interlanguage, or interwiki, linking within an\\\\\\\\narticle's body text is generally discouraged. Exceptions: Wiktionary\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wiktionary] and Wikisource [/wiki/Wikisource] entries may be linked\\\\\\\\ninline (e.g. to an unusual word or the text of a document being discussed), and\\\\\\\\n{{Interlanguage link [/wiki/Template:Interlanguage_link]}} template may be\\\\\\\\nhelpful to show a red link [/wiki/Wikipedia:RED] accompanied by an interlanguage\\\\\\\\nlink if no article exists in English Wikipedia.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFLOATING BOXES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Wikiquote-logo.svg/40px-Wikiquote-logo.svg.png]/wiki/File:Wikiquote-logo.svg\\\\\\\\nWikiquote has quotations related to Jimmy Wales\\\\\\\\n[https://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/Jimmy_Wales].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nFloating boxes for links to articles in other Wikimedia Foundation projects such\\\\\\\\nas Wiktionary and Wikiquote can be added using interwiki link sidebar templates\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Category:Interwiki_link_sidebar_templates], for example {{Wikiquote|Jimmy\\\\\\\\nWales}}. These display as a shaded box with a logo.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n(There is a related set of templates for some free content resources that are\\\\\\\\nnot run by the Wikimedia Foundation. Rather than creating a sidebar link, they\\\\\\\\ncreate text suitable for using as a bulleted entry in an \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"External links\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\nsection. A list of such templates can be found at Wikipedia:List of templates\\\\\\\\nlinking to other free content projects\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Wikipedia:List_of_templates_linking_to_other_free_content_projects].)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLINK MAINTENANCE\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nLinking and continual change are both central features of Wikipedia. However,\\\\\\\\ncontinual change makes linking vulnerable to acquired technical faults, and to\\\\\\\\nthe later provision of different information from that which was originally\\\\\\\\nintended. This is true of both \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"outgoing\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" links (from an article) and \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"incoming\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\nlinks (to an article).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Outgoing links: These should be checked from time to time for unintended\\\\\\\\n   changes that are undesirable. If the opportunity arises to improve their\\\\\\\\n   formatting, appropriateness, and focus, this should be done.\\\\\\\\n * Incoming links: Creating an article turns blue any existing red links to its\\\\\\\\n   title. Proper redlinks are created only in the hope that an article will\\\\\\\\n   eventually be written. Therefore, when creating an article, it is wise to\\\\\\\\n   check \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"What links here\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" to identify such redlinks, if any, and that they are\\\\\\\\n   appropriate.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nBUTTONS\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nShortcut [/wiki/Wikipedia:Shortcut]\\\\\\\\n * MOS:BUTTONS\\\\\\\\n   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=MOS:BUTTONS&redirect=no]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nButtons [/wiki/Button_(computing)] should not be used in articles. If the desire\\\\\\\\nis to \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"navigate\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" a reader to a new page, taking them away from the current page,\\\\\\\\na link is preferred. Buttons are used within Wikipedia to trigger an \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"action\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\nsuch as Show preview [/wiki/Help:Show_preview] or Create account\\\\\\\\n[/wiki/Special:CreateAccount] or Reply [/wiki/Help:Talk_pages#Getting_started]\\\\\\\\nor Ask a question [/wiki/Wikipedia:Help_desk].[3]\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSEE ALSO\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:Linking dos and don'ts [/wiki/Wikipedia:Linking_dos_and_don%27ts]\\\\\\\\n   (information page summarizing the key points of this guideline)\\\\\\\\n * Help:Interwikimedia links [/wiki/Help:Interwikimedia_links]\\\\\\\\n * Help:Menu/Links [/wiki/Help:Menu/Links]\\\\\\\\n * Template:Dead end [/wiki/Template:Dead_end]\\\\\\\\n * Template:Dead link [/wiki/Template:Dead_link]\\\\\\\\n * Template:Underlinked [/wiki/Template:Underlinked]\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:Dead-end pages [/wiki/Wikipedia:Dead-end_pages], pages without\\\\\\\\n   internal links\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:Integrate [/wiki/Wikipedia:Integrate]\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:Links to (disambiguation) pages\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:Links_to_(disambiguation)_pages]\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:Orphan [/wiki/Wikipedia:Orphan], pages without incoming links\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:Red link [/wiki/Wikipedia:Red_link]\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:Walled garden [/wiki/Wikipedia:Walled_garden]\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:What Wikipedia is not Wikipedia is not an indiscriminate\\\\\\\\n   collection of information\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:What_Wikipedia_is_not#Wikipedia_is_not_an_indiscriminate_collection_of_information]\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:Wikipedia doesn't use Allwiki\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_doesn%27t_use_Allwiki], the idea that every single\\\\\\\\n   word should be a link\\\\\\\\n * Wikipedia:WikiProject Orphanage [/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Orphanage],\\\\\\\\n   editors dedicated to clearing up the immense backlog of orphaned articles\\\\\\\\n * User:Tony1/Build your linking skills\\\\\\\\n   [/wiki/User:Tony1/Build_your_linking_skills], a tutorial on high-quality\\\\\\\\n   linking with practice questions\\\\\\\\n * User:Evad37/duplinks-alt [/wiki/User:Evad37/duplinks-alt], a script to\\\\\\\\n   highlight links occuring more than once in an article\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nNOTES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n 1. ^ Many, but not all, articles repeat the article title in bold face in the\\\\\\\\n    first line of the article. Linking the article to itself produces boldface\\\\\\\\n    text; this practice is discouraged as page moves result in a useless\\\\\\\\n    circular link through a redirect. Linking part of the bolded text is also\\\\\\\\n    discouraged because it changes the visual effect of bolding; some readers\\\\\\\\n    can miss the visual cue which is the purpose of using bold face in the first\\\\\\\\n    place.\\\\\\\\n 2. ^ If quoting hypertext that includes a Wikipedia link particularly salient\\\\\\\\n    to the quote's use, a [link in original] editorial note may be added. [link\\\\\\\\n    added] notes should generally be avoided, because if the clarification is\\\\\\\\n    needed badly enough to justify disrupting the flow of text, the link is\\\\\\\\n    probably not conservative and should be omitted.\\\\\\\\n 3. ^ A 2015 study of log data\\\\\\\\n    [https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Research:Improving_link_coverage] found\\\\\\\\n    that \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"in the English Wikipedia, of all the 800,000 links added ... in\\\\\\\\n    February 2015, the majority (66%) were not clicked even a single time in\\\\\\\\n    March 2015, and among the rest most links were clicked only very rarely\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\n    and that \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"simply adding more links does not increase the overall number of\\\\\\\\n    clicks taken from a page. Instead, links compete with each other for user\\\\\\\\n    attention.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" This was reported in: Paranjape, Ashwin; West, Bob; Leskovec,\\\\\\\\n    Jure; Zia, Leila (February 2225, 2016). \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Improving Website Hyperlink\\\\\\\\n    Structure Using Server Logs\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\". WSDM'16: Proceedings of the Ninth ACM\\\\\\\\n    International Conference on Web Search and Data Mining\\\\\\\\n    [http://infolab.stanford.edu/~west1/pubs/Paranjape-West-Leskovec-Zia_WSDM-16.pdf]\\\\\\\\n    (PDF). San Francisco: Association for Computing Machinery\\\\\\\\n    [/wiki/Association_for_Computing_Machinery]. doi\\\\\\\\n    [/wiki/Doi_(identifier)]:10.1145/2835776.2835832\\\\\\\\n    [https://doi.org/10.1145%2F2835776.2835832]. ISBN\\\\\\\\n    [/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)]9781450337168\\\\\\\\n    [/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781450337168].\\\\\\\\n 4. ^ Major sections are generally detailed sections with a level-2 heading, but\\\\\\\\n    consensus at an article may determine a lower-level subsection is major,\\\\\\\\n    especially when a preceding subsection is especially long, when an article's\\\\\\\\n    structure puts most content under level-3 headings with level-2 ones\\\\\\\\n    primarily used for thematic grouping, or when a subsection is a link target\\\\\\\\n    at which many readers arrive directly.\\\\\\\\n 5. ^ The hidden message (<!-- \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Article\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" links here -->) must be added to the\\\\\\\\n    target section with a break between the header and the hidden message, or\\\\\\\\n    problems arise. Note the two lines:\\\\\\\\n    ==Target section==\\\\\\\\n    <!-- \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Article\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" links here -->\\\\\\\\n    See MOS:HEADINGS [/wiki/MOS:HEADINGS] for further information about valid\\\\\\\\n    and invalid placement of heading comments.\\\\\\\\n 6. ^ Academic research has suggested that red links may be a driving force in\\\\\\\\n    Wikipedia growth; see: Spinellis, Diomidis [/wiki/Diomidis_Spinellis];\\\\\\\\n    Louridas, Panagiotis (2008). \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"The collaborative organization of knowledge\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\".\\\\\\\\n    Communications of the ACM [/wiki/Communications_of_the_ACM]. 51 (8).\\\\\\\\n    Association for Computing Machinery\\\\\\\\n    [/wiki/Association_for_Computing_Machinery]: 6873. doi\\\\\\\\n    [/wiki/Doi_(identifier)]:10.1145/1378704.1378720\\\\\\\\n    [https://doi.org/10.1145%2F1378704.1378720]. S2CID\\\\\\\\n    [/wiki/S2CID_(identifier)]77400\\\\\\\\n    [https://api.semanticscholar.org/CorpusID:77400]. Most new articles are\\\\\\\\n    created shortly after a corresponding reference to them is entered into the\\\\\\\\n    system See also Wikipedia:Inflationary hypothesis of Wikipedia growth\\\\\\\\n    [/wiki/Wikipedia:Inflationary_hypothesis_of_Wikipedia_growth].\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nREFERENCES\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n 1. ^ Dvorak, John C. [/wiki/John_C._Dvorak] (April 16, 2002). \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Missing Links\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n    [https://web.archive.org/web/20110806041207/https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,33326,00.asp].\\\\\\\\n    PC Magazine [/wiki/PC_Magazine]. Archived from the original\\\\\\\\n    [https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,1759,33326,00.asp] on August 6, 2011.\\\\\\\\n    Retrieved August 16, 2021.\\\\\\\\n 2. ^ \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"User:WhatamIdoing/Sandbox 3\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n    [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=User:WhatamIdoing/Sandbox_3&oldid=1136368242].\\\\\\\\n    Wikipedia (Englished.). January 30, 2023.
